{"title_page": "2010 Leinster Senior Football Championship Final", "text_new": "{{Use Irish English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|                   title = 2010 Leinster Football Final\n|                   image = \n|                   event = [[Leinster Senior Football Championship]]\n|                   team1 = [[Louth GAA|Louth]]\n|        team1association = [[File:Cork colours.PNG|40px]]\n|              team1score = 1\u201310\n|                   team2 = [[Meath GAA|Meath]]\n|        team2association = [[File:Donegal colours.jpg|40px]]\n|              team2score = 1\u201312\n|                 details =\n|                    date = 11 July 2010\n|                 stadium = [[Croke Park]]\n|                    city = [[Dublin]]\n|      man_of_the_match1a =\n|                 referee = [[Martin Sludden]] ([[Tyrone GAA|Tyrone]])\n|              attendance = 48,875<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/><ref name=\"GAME AT A GLANCE\"/>\n|                 weather =\n|                previous = [[2009 Leinster Senior Football Championship Final|2009]]\n|                    next = [[2011 Leinster Senior Football Championship Final|2011]]\n}}\nThe '''2010 Leinster Senior Football Championship Final''' was the last [[Gaelic football|football]] match of the 2010 [[Leinster Senior Football Championship]], played between [[Louth GAA|Louth]] and [[Meath GAA|Meath]] on 11 July 2010 in [[Croke Park]], Dublin.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0707/1224274220413.html|title=GAA \u2013 weekly fixtures|date=7 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=7 July 2010}}</ref> Louth were appearing in their first Leinster Senior Football Championship Final in 50 years. The game is memorable for its contentious conclusion, such that in 2020 it was described as \"the most controversial Leinster final ever\".<ref name=\"10 years later\"/>\n\nMeath won by 1\u201312 to 1\u201310, thanks to a controversial late goal by [[Joe Sheridan (Gaelic footballer)|Joe Sheridan]]. The goal was deemed illegal by television replays but was declared valid by referee Martin Sludden, from [[County Tyrone]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/8808677.stm|title=Referee Martin Sludden struck after Leinster decider|date=11 July 2010|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=11 July 2010}}</ref> He then blew the final whistle. Irate Louth fans stormed the [[Football pitch|pitch]] and commenced a process of chasing and physically assaulting the referee, who had to be led away by a [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na|Garda]] escort in scenes broadcast to a live television audience. Other scenes of violence saw bottles being hurled from a stand, one striking a steward who fell to the ground. The situation led to much media debate in the week that followed, the violence was condemned by senior politicians (some of whom were in the stadium), and there were calls for the game to be replayed\u2014though, ultimately, this did not happen.\n\nSe\u00e1n Moran of ''[[The Irish Times]]'' said the next day: \"What will be most vividly remembered of the 2010 final was compressed into a minute at the very end of the match with Louth getting ready to celebrate a deserved win \u2013 first over their neighbours in 35 years \u2013 and a resilient display\".<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\">{{cite news|author=Moran, Se\u00e1n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0712/1224274518802.html|title=Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> Colm Keys of the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' said it was \"hard to disagree\" that it was \"the greatest injustice for many a year in Croke Park\",<ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/sheridans-cruel-twist-denies-louth-2254831.html|title=Sheridan's cruel twist denies Louth|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> and remarked: \"The 320th anniversary of the [[Battle of the Boyne]] is being commemorated today, but that surely didn't throw up a talking point to match a Joe Sheridan goal that will have the counties divided by [[River Boyne|the same river]] at odds for years to come\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/fitzpatrick-slams-disgraceful-decision-2254830.html|title=Fitzpatrick slams 'disgraceful decision'|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==History of rivalry==\nLouth and Meath were rivals of old, both winning the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] in the 1950s; however, this was to be Louth's first appearance in the Leinster Senior Football Championship Final since a 1960 to [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]].<ref name=\"Meath will look to win midfield battle\">{{cite news|author=Moran, Se\u00e1n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0710/1224274420582.html|title=Meath will look to win midfield battle|date=10 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=10 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Border dispute with wee bit of history\"/> According to [[Colm O'Rourke]], \"there was a time in the late 1940s and '50s when Meath and Louth were the two best teams in the province [of Leinster] and played some memorable championship games\".<ref>{{cite news|author=O'Rourke, Colm|author-link=Colm O'Rourke|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/colm-orourke/colm-orourke-great-rivals-of-the-dim-and-distant-past-are-reunitedbut-louths-fairytale-day-wont-have-a-happy-ending-2254156.html|title=Great rivals of the dim and distant past are reunitedbut Louth's fairytale day won't have a happy ending|date=11 July 2010|work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=11 July 2010}}</ref> Keith Duggan of ''The Irish Times'' reported that the two teams \"fight like alley cats\".<ref name=\"Border dispute with wee bit of history\">{{cite news|author=Duggan, Keith|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0710/1224274420598.html|title=Border dispute with wee bit of history|date=10 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=10 July 2010}}</ref> They had last met four years previously in a preliminary round of the Leinster Senior Football Championship, with Meath emerging victorious.<ref name=\"Meath will look to win midfield battle\"/> Louth had last defeated Meath in 1975, also at Croke Park.<ref name=\"Meath will look to win midfield battle\"/> Three matches were required to produce a winner when the two encountered each other in July 1949.<ref name=\"Border dispute with wee bit of history\"/> Other meetings include a draw in a semi-final of the 1951 Leinster Senior Football Championship, with Meath narrowly winning the replay.<ref name=\"Border dispute with wee bit of history\"/> Meath also defeated Louth in the 1952 Leinster Senior Football Championship Final.<ref name=\"Border dispute with wee bit of history\"/> Following on from Louth's aforementioned 1975 victory, there were other Meath wins in 1998, 2002 and 2006.<ref name=\"Border dispute with wee bit of history\"/>\n\n==Route to the final==\n'''Preliminary Round:''' Louth 1\u201311 [[Longford GAA|Longford]] 1\u20137; Meath 1\u201320 Offaly 2\u20137<br />\n'''Quarter-finals:''' Louth 1\u201322 [[Kildare GAA|Kildare]] 1\u201316; Meath 2\u201314 [[Laois GAA|Laois]] 0\u201310<br />\n'''Semi-finals:''' Louth 1\u201315 [[Westmeath GAA|Westmeath]] 2\u201310; Meath 5\u20139 [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] 0\u201313\n\n==Pre-match==\n\n===Team selection===\nOn 9 July, both teams announced their teams for the final.<ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0709/1224274348043.html|title=Kenny resumes his position in central role|date=9 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=9 July 2010|quote=Both Meath and Louth will today release their starting line-ups for Sunday's Leinster football final in Croke Park \u2013 and while Louth are likely to be unchanged from their semi-final win over Westmeath, Meath are expected to start Nigel Crawford at midfield, the only likely switch from the team which ripped Dublin apart in their semi-final.}}</ref> Meath announced their team first, with captain [[Nigel Crawford]], returning after injury, replacing [[Mark Ward (Meath GAA footballer born 1985)|Mark Ward]] in midfield.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0709/1224274378545.html|title=Crawford to start against Louth|date=9 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=9 July 2010|quote=Nigel Crawford comes into the Meath midfield for Sunday's Leinster final against Louth. Crawford, who has fully recovered from a back injury, will start alongside Brian Meade in the Meath engine room with Mark Ward making way. Louth manager Peter Fitzpatrick will announce his team later today.}}</ref>\n\n===Attendance===\nIt was anticipated beforehand that attendance would be at its lowest of the decade, estimated at 45,000 or 50,000 by Ian O'Riordan of ''The Irish Times''.<ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0709/1224274348000.html|title=Lowest crowd in decade due for final|date=9 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=9 July 2010}}</ref> 48,875 people attended the game.<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/><ref name=\"GAME AT A GLANCE\"/> The issue of applying fencing around Croke Park to prevent pitch invasions had been discussed prior to the game.<ref>{{cite news|author=Moran, Se\u00e1n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0706/1224274102516.html|title=McKenna reiterates warning on fencing|date=6 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=6 July 2010|quote=Last Sunday, saw Kilkenny retain their provincial title against Galway without problems but a county winning a sixth successive provincial title is unlike to spark the same reaction as next weekend when Meath, for the first time in nine years, or Louth, for the first time in 50, will raise the Leinster football trophy.}}</ref> The violent scenes which followed the 2010 Leinster Senior Football Championship Final renewed this debate in the days afterwards,<ref name=\"Referee admits error in awarding Meath goal\"/><ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0713/1224274590265.html|title=GAA say fencing would be last resort|date=13 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> though President Cooney later said \"the last thing we want to do is put fencing up around Croke Park\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0720/cooneyc.html |title=Cooney confirms pitch presentations |date=20 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=20 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722063726/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0720/cooneyc.html |archivedate=22 July 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0720/1224275100231.html|title=GAA plans for on-pitch presentations|date=20 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=20 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\nLouth's [[JP Rooney]] and [[Shane Lennon]] both missed opportunities in the first half.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0711/1224274490689.html|title=Rough justice for heartbroken Louth|date=11 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=11 July 2010}}</ref> Louth dominated the second half, though spurned numerous opportunities to take a commanding lead over Meath.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> Rooney scored a goal with seven minutes of the game left.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> Meath converted two long-range free kicks from [[Cian Ward]], but Louth still led by one point in the final minute.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> Louth's [[Colm Judge]] was sent off in the 69th minute for a second bookable offence.<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/><ref name=\"GAME AT A GLANCE\"/> Then came the controversial goal by [[Joe Sheridan (Gaelic footballer)|Joe Sheridan]] in the third minute of stoppage time.<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/> The ball was kicked into the square by Graham Reilly. It came out to [[Seamus Kenny (footballer)|Seamus Kenny]], who could have gone for the point, but saw a goal chance and shot. But the ball was blocked by Louth captain [[Paddy Keenan]], and fell into the square, towards Louth full-back [[Dessie Finnegan]]. But Finnegan failed to clear and the ball went straight to Joe Sheridan, who fell over the goal line and then threw the ball into the net \u2013 both illegal moves.<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/> Sheridan was also \"inside the square\" at the time the ball reached him, in a third illegal move. Yet the goal was allowed and all of a sudden Meath were winning by two points.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> Referee Sludden checked with the umpire and did not change his mind,<ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/> blowing his whistle for full-time soon after with the score at Meath 1\u201312: Louth 1\u201310, much to the disappointment of everyone associated with Louth.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> TV replays immediately demonstrated that the referee was incorrect when he awarded the goal to Meath.<ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/>\n\n===Violence===\nLouth fans poured onto the pitch to express their feelings to the referee,<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/><ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/> and, in the words of ''The Irish Times'', \"all hell broke loose\".<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> At least four fans physically attacked Sludden and struck him with violence.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/><ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/><ref name=\"Dark clouds cast over Louth's big day in the sun\"/> One man who was wearing a red shirt shoved Sludden in the chest before being pursued by television cameras as he made his departure.<ref>{{cite news|author1=McGarry, Patsy  |author2=Lally, Conor|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/0712/1224274518490.html|title=Referee shoved in chest after GAA final|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010|quote=THERE WERE no arrests in Croke Park yesterday despite unruly scenes at the end of the Leinster football final between Louth and Meath in which referee Martin Sludden was pushed and jostled. [...] A man in a red shirt rushed onto the field and shoved the referee in the chest. He was followed by RT\u00c9 cameras as he left the scene.}}</ref> Sludden was awarded a [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na|Garda]] escort as he made haste his escape from the pitch.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/><ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/> Stadium director Peter McKenna said the referee was \"very shaken\" after his experience.<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/>\n\nLouth manager [[Peter Fitzpatrick]] intervened to physically urge the fans to halt their behaviour,<ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0711/crokerpark_meath_louth.html |title=Referee is attacked in Croke Park |date=11 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=11 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100712234014/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0711/crokerpark_meath_louth.html |archivedate=12 July 2010 }}</ref> an act later described by the ''Irish Independent'' as \"a remarkable display of composure from the [[Dundalk]] man, who had every right to be spitting feathers at the defeat\".<ref name=\"Bookies' handout eases Louth pain\"/> Meath substitute [[Mark Ward (Meath GAA footballer born 1985)|Mark Ward]] was hit by a Louth fan.<ref name=\"10 Key questions after Sunday's chaotic scenes at Croker\"/> Children cried and looked sad, and one child allegedly received a wound when hit by a steward.<ref name=\"Gardai close in on Croker prosecutions\"/> Bottles were hurled from the stands.<ref name=\"Dark clouds cast over Louth's big day in the sun\"/> A steward also received wounds when he was assaulted by a soft drinks bottle.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/><ref name=\"Meath call for extra time over Louth replay bid\"/> He was given medical attention,<ref name=\"Dark clouds cast over Louth's big day in the sun\"/> and later declared fit to steward further matches.<ref name=\"Meath call for extra time over Louth replay bid\"/>\n\nElsewhere in the stadium, former Meath All-Ireland Senior Football Championship-winning manager [[Se\u00e1n Boylan]] was involved in an altercation with an irate Louth fan in a corporate box.<ref name=\"Boylan plays down incident with Louth fan\">{{cite news|author=McHale, Michael|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/boylan-plays-down-incident-with-louth-fan-2254940.html|title=Boylan plays down incident with Louth fan|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Boylan plays down incident with Louth fan\"/> Boylan said: \"People lose the head all the time\" and that he was \"more embarrassed than anything\".<ref name=\"Boylan plays down incident with Louth fan\"/>\n\n===Details===\n{{football box\n|date=11 July 2010\n|time = 14:00 [[Irish Summer Time|UTC+1]]\n|team1 = [[Louth GAA|Louth]]\n|score = 1\u201310 \u2013 1\u201312\n|report = [http://www.gaa.ie/gaa-news-and-videos/news-archive/1107101654-royals-late-show-breaks-wee-hearts/ (Report)]\n|team2 = [[Meath GAA|Meath]]\n|goals1 = P Keenan (0-1), B White (0-4, 3f), A McDonnell (0-1), A Reed (0-1), C Judge (0-2, 1f), JP Rooney (1-1)\n|goals2 =  A Moyles (0-1), N Crawford (0-1), J Sheridan (1-0), G Reilly (0-4), C Ward (0-4, 4f), S Bray (0-2)\n|stadium = [[Croke Park]], Dublin\n|attendance = 48,875<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/><ref name=\"GAME AT A GLANCE\"/>\n|referee = [[Martin Sludden]]\n}}\n\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = _whiteshoulders\n |pattern_b  = _thinwhitesides\n |pattern_ra = _whiteshoulders\n |leftarm    = ff0000\n |body       = ff0000\n |rightarm   = ff0000\n |shorts     = FFFFFF\n |socks      = ff0000\n |title      = Louth\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = yellowshoulders\n |pattern_b  = _thinyellowsides\n |pattern_ra = _yellowshoulders\n |leftarm    = 28AE7B\n |body       = 28AE7B\n |rightarm   = 28AE7B\n |shorts     = FFFFFF\n |socks      = 28AE7B\n |title      = Meath\n}}\n|}\n\n==View of match participants==\n\n===Joe Sheridan===\nJoe Sheridan, who scored the controversial goal, described how he had done it: \"It was well-worked and it was a definite goal. People are saying I threw it in, but I was heading for the line and I just dropped the ball and it was in the net. I got it and the lad just pushed me into the net. I tried to do whatever I could to hit it and the goal was given, simple as that. I was pushed in over the line so it should have been a penalty anyway. I think it was a perfect goal\".<ref name=\"Little sympathy in Meath camp\"/>\n\n===Match officials===\nReferee Martin Sludden later admitted he had made an error.<ref name=\"Referee admits error in awarding Meath goal\"/><ref name=\"10 Key questions after Sunday's chaotic scenes at Croker\"/> His referee's report acknowledged a \"terrible mistake\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0715/1224274738230.html|title=Louth move on but sense of injustice persists|date=15 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=15 July 2010|quote=In the light of this and the clear admission in the referee's report that he \"made a terrible mistake\", the referee's report therefore is questionable. [...] We would contend that the committee/ council in charge erred in leaving the matter to Meath County Board to offer a replay, without seeking clarification from the referee in relation to his match report and his statement \"he made a terrible mistake\".}}</ref> However, based on past refereeing errors, his place on the panel of 18 referees to officiate during the 2010 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship was secure, though the likelihood of him refereeing another match was less so.<ref name=\"10 Key questions after Sunday's chaotic scenes at Croker\">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/10-key-questions-after-sundays-chaotic-scenes-at-croker-2255907.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130111155028/http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/10-key-questions-after-sundays-chaotic-scenes-at-croker-2255907.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 January 2013 |title=10 Key questions after Sunday's chaotic scenes at Croker |date=13 July 2010 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 }}</ref> It was thought likely he had been deducted four points from one hundred for his error by his assessor (1 for missing a foul and 3 for Meath profiting from it with a score), though rules banning the assessor from looking at video evidence meant Sludden may not have been deducted any points if the assessor could not see the incident properly from the stand.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Kelly, Liam  |author2=Foley, Cliona|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/bullish-gilroy-unrepentant-after-depriving-daly-of-dual-star-ocarroll-2262636.html|title=Bullish Gilroy unrepentant after depriving Daly of dual star O'Carroll|date=17 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=17 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Team managers===\nLouth manager Peter Fitzpatrick said he was \"absolutely devastated\" on RT\u00c9.<ref name=\"Meath county board asks for more time\"/> Appearing later on radio station [[LMFM]], he described the referee as \"[[Dick Turpin]] without a mask\", adding \"It was pure daylight robbery. I'm very, very annoyed\".<ref name=\"Little sympathy in Meath camp\"/>\n\nWhen questioned at a press conference about Sheridan's goal, Meath manager Eamon O'Brien said: \"I can't say and I'm not commenting. I can comment, as I said to RT\u00c9, that loads of decisions were made during the game that didn't go our way. I can recall three or four balls that were blown for picking off the ground that I didn\u2019t think were off the ground. Nigel Crawford was booked up here and Louth got a point off it. The game goes for 70 minutes, decisions are made and you live with it. That\u2019s it, that\u2019s the way I see it\".<ref name=\"Little sympathy in Meath camp\"/>\n\n===Other players===\nMeath's captain Nigel Crawford gave his opinion on the incident: \"I'm sure most players have been involved in controversial situations like that where you get calls for replays and things like that happening, but I just don't think it's possible or I just don't think it can happen. If you start that, where do you end up? Do we go back and say the ball wasn\u2019t on the ground when we touched it and they got a free or whatever? It's just very unfortunate that it happens in a high-profile game right at the end of a game to a team that hasn't won in a long time. It's just a very unfortunate situation\".<ref name=\"Little sympathy in Meath camp\"/>\n\nLouth player J. P. Rooney said: \"Aaron Hoey was pleading with [Sludden] to consult with his umpires but when he went in, he told them to put up the green flag. [...] I know it's wrong, people running at the ref, but you can see why Louth people did it. He brought it on himself and I wouldn't feel sorry for him\".<ref name=\"Who said what . . .\"/>\n\n==Reaction==\n\n===Media===\nThe ''Irish Independent'' said \"Meath's Leinster Final goal-that-never-was will go down in history \u2013 and not only in Ireland, since by now the images have flashed round the world \u2013 among the great injustices suffered in any sport\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/editorial/gaa-must-play-fair-by-louth-2255101.html|title=GAA must play fair by Louth|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> ''The Irish Times'' described \"ugly scenes\",<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> with Damian Cullen calling it \"one of the strangest endings ever to a GAA match\",<ref name=\"September Road\"/> Se\u00e1n Moran describing it as \"the most extraordinary refereeing error since Jimmy Cooney whistled up early 12 years ago\",<ref name=\"Little sympathy in Meath camp\">{{cite news|author=Moran, Se\u00e1n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0712/1224274518857.html|title=Little sympathy in Meath camp|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> and the newspaper publishing numerous letters on the topic from disgruntled members of the public every day that week.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/letters/2010/0713/1224274589427.html|title=Controversy over Leinster final|date=13 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/letters/2010/0714/1224274657571.html|title=Controversy over Leinster final|date=14 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/letters/2010/0715/1224274739007.html|title=Controversy over Leinster final|date=15 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/letters/2010/0716/1224274821598.html|title=Controversy over Leinster final|date=16 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=16 July 2010}}</ref> The same newspaper's Philip Reid remarked upon the coincidence that these events had occurred on the same day as the [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final]] in South Africa, wondered why goal-line technology could not be used and added: \"On this point, it would appear, the GAA and [[FIFA]] have something in common: they live in the times of the dinosaur\".<ref name=\"Dark clouds cast over Louth's big day in the sun\">{{cite news|author=Reid, Philip|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0712/1224274518576.html|title=Dark clouds cast over Louth's big day in the sun|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> The events in Croke Park led to less prominent newspaper coverage of the FIFA World Cup Final itself the next day.<ref name=\"10 Key questions after Sunday's chaotic scenes at Croker\"/> The incident surrounding the goal was likened to [[Thierry Henry]]'s illegal handball in the [[2009 Republic of Ireland vs France football matches|France vs Republic of Ireland 2010 FIFA World Cup play-off]].<ref name=\"September Road\">{{cite news|author=Cullen, Damian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0712/1224274518850.html|title=September Road|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010|quote=AFTER Joe \"Thierry Henry\" Sheridan's controversial handling of the ball at the end of yesterday's Leinster final, we wracked our brains for some of the other controversial and bizarre endings to GAA matches.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Watterson, Johnny|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0717/1224274900960.html|title=Hold the back page|date=17 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=17 July 2010|quote=The unravelling of the Leinster football final sparked off radical suggestions the match should be replayed and while not as globally embarrassing as the FAI whimpering over the Thierry Henry hand ball, it seemed equally absurd. While Meath diplomacy forbids them to ridicule the \"Replayistas\" in the manner Fifa boss Sepp Blatter did with the FAI, be sure Meath players bridled at the suggestion.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Bray, Allison  |author2=Keys, Colm  |author3=Clarke, Denise  |last-author-amp=yes|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/mayhem-and-madness-as-fans-attack-referee-2254900.html|title=Mayhem and madness as fans attack referee|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010|quote=Meath chairman Barney Allen refused to be drawn on a potential offer of a replay afterwards, drawing comparison with the Irish soccer team's plight last November after the Thierry Henry handball. \"Ireland didn't get a replay when France got a lucky goal,\" said Mr Allen.}}</ref> Public service broadcaster RT\u00c9 referred to \"disgraceful scenes\".<ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/> The GAA website's official match report brushed aside the controversy, saying Sheridan had \"smuggled the ball over the line\".<ref name=\"September Road\"/> [[Eugene McGee (Gaelic football manager)|Eugene McGee]], writing in the ''Irish Independent'', said \"It will be a stain on the good name of the GAA if this result is allowed to stand\".<ref>{{cite news|author=McGee, Eugene|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/eugene-mcgee/eugene-mcgee-if-fair-play-exists-in-the-gaa-louth-should-get-their-replay-2254833.html|title=If fair play exists in the gaa, Louth should get their replay|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> His colleague [[Martin Breheny]] said there ought to be no replay and that \"no sport can run its affairs on the basis of sentiment\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Breheny, Martin|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/we-cant-replay-gaa-has-no-room-for-sentiment-2257325.html|title=We can't replay \u2013 GAA has no room for sentiment|date=14 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===GAA administrators===\nThe following day, the GAA released a statement confirming that Sludden admitted he had made an error.<ref name=\"Referee admits error in awarding Meath goal\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0712/meath_louth1.html |title=Referee admits error in awarding Meath goal |date=12 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=12 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714155354/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0712/meath_louth1.html |archivedate=14 July 2010 }}</ref> The GAA also stated that the rules left it powerless to offer a replay and that this would be decided by Meath,<ref name=\"Referee admits error in awarding Meath goal\"/><ref name=\"10 Key questions after Sunday's chaotic scenes at Croker\"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Moran, Se\u00e1n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0712/1224274518866.html|title=Replay only possible if Royal offer is made|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> though most Meath players did not wish to facilitate a replay,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0713/meath_louth.html |title=Royals reluctant to offer Louth replay |date=13 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714155404/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0713/meath_louth.html |archivedate=14 July 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/8812395.stm|title=Louth hopes of replay fade after Meath players say 'no'|date=13 July 2010|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> while former Meath players were said to be in favour of one.<ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/meath-buy-time-2256002.html|title=Meath buy time. . . but players and management likely to put an end to Louth's replay hopes|date=13 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> The GAA said it would work with the authorities to capture Sludden's attackers.<ref name=\"Referee admits error in awarding Meath goal\"/>\n\n[[List of Presidents of the Gaelic Athletic Association|GAA President]] [[Christy Cooney]] said the events were a \"watershed\" and one where the \"circumstances were bizarre. I have never seen circumstances like it as long as I have been a member of this Association\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0716/cooney.html |title=Cooney \u2013 Leinster final a watershed for GAA |date=16 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=16 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717195114/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0716/cooney.html |archivedate=17 July 2010 }}</ref> He promised life bans for those who assaulted the referee.<ref>{{cite news|author=Foley, Cliona |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/we-will-impose-life-bans-cooney-2262817.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802073852/http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/we-will-impose-life-bans-cooney-2262817.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 2 August 2012 |title=We will impose life bans: Cooney |date=17 July 2010 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |accessdate=17 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nCroke Park's stadium director Peter McKenna questioned why Louth manager Peter Fitzpatrick had walked onto the pitch to ask the referee about the decision.<ref name=\"Dark clouds cast over Louth's big day in the sun\"/> [[Gaelic Players Association]] (GPA) chief executive [[Dessie Farrell]] said: \"What went on last Sunday was a PR disaster for us all\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/louth-facing-decision-on-use-of-navan-as-home-venue-2260931.html|title=Louth facing decision on use of Navan as 'home' venue|date=16 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=16 July 2010}}</ref> The National Referees Committee gave a negative response to the idea of goal-line technology being used in future.<ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0713/1224274590243.html|title=Referees in no rush for video technology|date=13 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> Retired referee [[John Bannon (referee)|John Bannon]] said \"No one deserves to be attacked, either verbally or physically, especially in Croke Park. [...] This attitude still remains part of the GAA's culture, it has never been rooted out\".<ref name=\"Who said what . . .\">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/who-said-what-2255909.html|title=Who said what . . .|date=13 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> [[Tyrone GAA|Tyrone]] County Board (from where the referee originated) sympathised with the Sludden but said the crowd's reaction was \"unbelievable\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Cahill, Jackie|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/red-hand-chairman-standing-by-underfire-ref-sludden-2259098.html|title=Red Hand chairman standing by under-fire ref Sludden|date=15 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> [[Liam O'Neill]], a candidate for the GAA presidency in 2012, later said: \"Quite simply, there should have been a re-fixture for that game. Everyone knows that. Everyone knows a wrong was perpetrated\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Cummiskey, Gavin|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0721/1224275144935.html|title=O'Neill calls for change to five-year term on playing laws|date=21 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=21 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===GAA personalities===\nThere was significant public and analytical support for Louth and condemnation of the refereeing decision.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0712/meath_louth.html |title=Massive support for Wee County |date=12 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=12 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714155349/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0712/meath_louth.html |archivedate=14 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn ''[[The Sunday Game]]'' TV highlights programme, [[Pat Spillane]] called both the fans and the referee \"disgraceful\", commenting: {{cquote|Those were disgraceful scenes at the end. Cowardly individuals attacking a referee who is doing it in a voluntary capacity. There is no place in the GAA for people like that. Scandalous scenes and a bad day for the GAA on that account. A fella doing a job made a human error. He made a mistake. We cannot condone those scenes, they are disgraceful and punishments must be handed out. However, just as disgraceful is that Louth were robbed of their first Leinster title since 1957 by a complete refereeing mistake. Joe Sheridan threw the ball over the line. Under any rules of the game, experimental or not, the goal should not have been allowed.<ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/>}}\n\nFormer Meath player [[Trevor Giles]] said: \"If this victory stands, it won't do Meath any favours because there will always be a question mark over the result\".<ref name=\"Who said what . . .\"/> Former [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] footballer [[Darragh \u00d3 S\u00e9]] described the idea of Meath County Board having the final decision on a replay as \"a complete and utter cop-out\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0714/1224274657319.html|title=Controversies highlight that the GAA must start to show some direction|date=14 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref> Former Kerry footballer and manager [[P\u00e1id\u00ed \u00d3 S\u00e9]] said: \"there is no way any referee should have allowed Sheridan's goal to stand\".<ref>{{cite news|author=\u00d3 S\u00e9, P\u00e1id\u00ed|author-link=P\u00e1id\u00ed \u00d3 S\u00e9|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/in-sport-you-have-to-take-the-rough-with-the-smooth-2263257.html|title=In sport, you have to take the rough with the smooth|date=18 July 2010|work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=18 July 2010}}</ref> [[Sligo GAA|Sligo]] footballer [[Eamonn O'Hara]] suggested that the events gave \"the perfect opportunity [for the GAA] to revamp the way match-day officials are selected\".<ref>{{cite news|author=O'Hara, Eamonn|author-link=Eamonn O'Hara|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/leinster-final-chaos-presents-perfect-chance-to-revamp-umpire-selection-2263884.html|title=Leinster final chaos presents perfect chance to revamp umpire selection|date=19 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nVeteran commentator [[M\u00edche\u00e1l \u00d3 Muircheartaigh]] told [[Ryan Tubridy]] on [[The Tubridy Show|his radio show]] that \"Croke Park abdicated responsibility. They should have taken the matter from Meath\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Keane, Billy|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/gaarsquos-abdication-of-responsibility-towards-royals-has-tarnished-their-leinster-crown-2262810.html|title=GAA's abdication of responsibility towards Royals has tarnished their Leinster crown|date=17 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=17 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Politicians===\n[[Minister for Justice and Equality|Minister for Justice and Law Reform]] [[Dermot Ahern]], himself from Louth, made known his condemnation of the violence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.examiner.ie/breakingnews/ireland/justice-minister-condemns-altercations-at-gaa-game-465189.html|title=Justice Minister condemns altercations at GAA game|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|publisher=[[Thomas Crosbie Holdings]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> He attended the match.<ref name=\"Ahern deplores Croke Park scenes\">{{cite news|author1=Parsons, Michael  |author2=Minihan, Mary|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/0713/1224274589396.html|title=Ahern deplores Croke Park scenes|date=13 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> [[Taoiseach]] [[Brian Cowen]] also made known his disapproval later from New York: \"I didn't see what happened as the ref was leaving the pitch. But obviously none of that is justified. It was an exciting match obviously. But it doesn't justify anyone engaging in that sort of activity. So I wouldn't like to see it repeated anywhere\".<ref name=\"Ahern deplores Croke Park scenes\"/> Cowen was also at the match.<ref name=\"Ahern deplores Croke Park scenes\"/>\n\n===Other===\nThe [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na]] announced that it would investigate those persons they said breached the Non-fatal Offences Against the Person Act by battering the referee and others.<ref name=\"Gardai close in on Croker prosecutions\">{{cite news|author1=Cusack, Jim  |author2=Lawlor, Damian|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/gardai-close-in-on-croker-prosecutions-2263264.html|title=Garda\u00ed close in on Croker prosecutions|date=18 July 2010|work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=18 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nBookmaker [[Boylesports]] paid all losing bets on the match.<ref name=\"Bookies' handout eases Louth pain\">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/bookies-handout-eases-louth-pain-2254846.html|title=Bookies' handout eases Louth pain|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Outcome==\nOn 13 July, Louth's county executive committee issued a statement condemning what it described as \"the unsavoury incidents after the match\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0713/louth_meath.html |title=Louth condemn Croke Park attack |date=13 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714155359/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0713/louth_meath.html |archivedate=14 July 2010 }}</ref> Meath's county board gathered in [[Navan]] but did not issue an immediate statement, instead requesting more time to think.<ref name=\"Meath call for extra time over Louth replay bid\">{{cite news|author1=Keys, Colm |author2=McHale, Michael |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/meath-call-for-extra-time-over-louth-replay-bid-2255978.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130108004530/http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/meath-call-for-extra-time-over-louth-replay-bid-2255978.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 8 January 2013 |title=Meath call for extra time over Louth replay bid |date=13 July 2010 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"Meath county board asks for more time\">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0712/1224274552634.html|title=Meath county board asks for more time|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0713/1224274590229.html|title=Meath's deferral of final decision makes chance of replay less likely|date=13 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> They later decided that there would be no replay, this would be \"the end of the matter\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0713/1224274613334.html|title=Meath decide against offering replay|date=13 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> Meath were officially champions of Leinster for 2010,<ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0714/1224274680949.html|title=Louth left to ponder options|date=14 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=14 July 2010|quote=In the end they delivered on the greater expectation that the result must, under GAA rule, still stand, and that, as far as they were concerned, \"was the end of the matter\". It means Meath go forward as Leinster football champions, in name at least.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0714/1224274660841.html|title=Meath rule out replay to leave Louth pondering options|date=14 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref> though Meath secretary Cyril Creavin conceded that it was a \"tainted\" title and that \"Some of the players are devastated with the reaction in newspapers\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/louths-legal-move-2257402.html|title=Louth's legal move|date=14 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/8820138.stm|title=Louth hopes of replay end as Meath board says 'no'|date=14 July 2010|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref> Louth accepted this: their official statement referred to the [[July 2010 R238 traffic collision]] which occurred on the same day as the final, sympathising with relatives of the eight people killed, and opting to avoid legal action in such a context.<ref name=\"Louth to take no further action\"/> Therefore, Meath automatically entered the quarter-finals of the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]], with Louth left to qualify for that same stage by playing (and winning) a further game in Round 4<ref name=\"GAME AT A GLANCE\">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/game-at-a-glance-2254832.html|title=GAME AT A GLANCE|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> of the All-Ireland qualifiers.<ref name=\"Louth to take no further action\">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0714/1224274728235.html|title=Louth to take no further action|date=14 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=14 July 2010|quote=\u201cFinally, in light of [[July 2010 R238 traffic collision|the tragic events which occurred in Donegal over the weekend]] we realise that we must put our situation in context and we would like to extend our deepest sympathies to the family and friends of those deceased.\"}}</ref>\n\nLouth were drawn against [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] in their next game.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0719/1224275061957.html|title=Louth get Croke Park date with Dublin|date=19 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0719/1224275033301.html|title=Louth draw qualifier date with Dublin|date=19 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0719/1224275017767.html|title=Roscommon shine once again as Sligo can't live up to expectations|date=19 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=19 July 2010|quote=The big question about the Dublin-Louth pairing is how well Louth can recover from last Sunday's Leinster final fiasco against Meath, because unless they come out fighting again, Dublin have a great chance of making the All-Ireland quarter-final.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0721/1224275145109.html|title=Fitzpatrick delighted with 'dream' draw|date=21 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=21 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/louth-must-pick-up-pieces-as-resurgent-dublin-await-in-qualifiers-2263873.html|title=Louth must pick up pieces as resurgent Dublin await in qualifiers|date=19 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref> The appointment of experienced referee [[Pat McEnaney]] was scrutinised and praised in advance.<ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/mcenaney-to-take-charge-of-louthdublin-croker-clash-2265916.html|title=McEnaney to take charge of Louth-Dublin Croker clash|date=21 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=21 July 2010|quote=McEnaney's appointment will be viewed as a secure option after the dramatic and tension-filled scenes at the end of the Leinster football final at the same venue 10 days ago.}}</ref> In the game, held once again at Croke Park on 24 July,<ref>{{cite news|author=Cummiskey, Gavin|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0720/1224275073430.html|title=It's double headers back to back|date=20 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=20 July 2010|quote=The Dublin footballers, as expected and despite the low turnouts for their recent victories over Tipperary and Armagh, are back in Croke Park for a fifth time this season, and third successive week, as they attempt to salvage their campaign against Louth. That means the defeated Leinster finalists must return to the scene of the crime that saw referee Martin Sludden assaulted by supporters after the provincial decider against Meath on July 11th.}}</ref> Louth were defeated by 2\u201314 to 0\u201313, thus being eliminated from the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 2010|2010 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0724/1224275433712.html|title=Dublin show no sympathy|date=24 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=24 July 2010|quote=Moral champions of Leinster they maybe but Louth are out of the All-Ireland football championship after being comprehensively beaten by Dublin at Croke Park. Two weeks after being denied a provincial title by a very bad call against Meath, the Wee County can have few complaints this time round.}}</ref><ref name=\"Dubs finally warming to summer task\">{{cite news|author=Crowe, Dermot|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/dubs-finally-warming-to-summer-task-2271850.html|title=Dubs finally warming to summer task|date=25 July 2010|work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=25 July 2010|quote=Two weeks after they were stunned in the Leinster final, Louth still looked punch-drunk as the Dubs raced into an early lead, boosted by a goal from Eoghan O'Gara. They never recovered and the game limped to an inevitable conclusion. After the final whistle they went on a lap of honour to offer appreciation to their followers after the longest summer the county has witnessed in over half a century.}}</ref> By defeating Louth, Dublin joined Meath in the quarter-finals of the All-Ireland Senior Football Championship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0724/dublin_louth.html |title=Dublin 2\u201314 Louth 0\u201313 |date=24 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=24 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724232452/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0724/dublin_louth.html |archivedate=24 July 2010 }}</ref> For Louth so ended \"the longest summer the county has witnessed in over half a century\".<ref name=\"Dubs finally warming to summer task\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nLouth manager Fitzpatrick found success as a national politician; he was elected as a [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]] at the [[2011 Irish general election|2011 general election]] and re-elected several times after that.<ref name=\"10 years later\"/> He continued as Louth manager until after the 2012 season, at which point he left.<ref name=\"10 years later\"/>\n\nOn 15 September 2014, \"A Wee Royal Rumble - The Story of the 2010 Leinster Football Final\" was broadcast on [[RT\u00c9 One]] as part of ''[[Scannal]]'', the TV series dedicated to scandalous events.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hoganstand.com/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=224348|title=If it happened to Meath I'm sure the referee would have ended up in the canal|work=Hogan Stand|date=15 September 2014|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nNearly ten years later, in a newspaper article published on [[Easter|Easter Sunday]], Fitzpatrick - who had earlier watched the match for just the third time since (the first having been the night it was played) - stated that he had seen referee Sludden only once since: \"I went to [[Murder of Michaela McAreavey|Michaela Harte's funeral]] [in mid-January 2011] and he was ahead of me in the queue. That's the only time. I have never seen or{{sic}} spoken to him since\".<ref name=\"10 years later\">{{cite news|author=Crowe, Dermot|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/we-will-never-forget-the-11th-of-july-2010-peter-fitzpatrick-brian-white-and-joe-sheridan-reflect-on-a-day-that-shook-the-gaa-39103138.html|title='We will never forget the 11th of July 2010' - Peter Fitzpatrick, Brian White and Joe Sheridan reflect on a day that shook the GAA|date=5 April 2020|work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]|accessdate=5 April 2020|quote=A fortnight after the most controversial Leinster final ever, Kildare overpowered them [Meath].}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Vincent Hogan|Hogan, Vincent]]. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/vincent-hogan/vincent-hogan-sport-cant-force-social-values-it-reflects-them-2255842.html \"Sport can't force social values \u2013 it reflects them\"]. ''[[Irish Independent]]''. Tuesday, 13 July 2010.\n* Keys, Colm. [http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/the-fact-is-that-scenes-like-this-are-part-and-parcel-of-gaa-culture-2256001.html \"The fact is that scenes like this are part and parcel of GAA culture\"]. ''Irish Independent''. Tuesday, 13 July 2010.\n* Boyle, Donnchadh. [http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/leo-turley-2257320.html \"Leo Turley: Laois '95\"]. ''Irish Independent''. Wednesday, 14 July 2010.\n* Keys, Colm. [http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/the-great-hypocrisy-2257323.html \"The great hypocrisy\"]. ''Irish Independent''. Wednesday, 14 July 2010.\n* Devlin, Martina. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/martina-devlin/martina-devlin-stubborn-gaa-has-failed-its-referees-and-the-sport-2259059.html \"Stubborn GAA has failed its referees and the sport\"]. ''Irish Independent''. Thursday, 15 July 2010.\n* [[Martin Breheny|Breheny, Martin]]. [http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/net-gains-2259100.html \"Net gains\"]. ''Irish Independent''. Thursday, 15 July 2010.\n* Lynch, Declan. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/unsporting-conduct-on-and-off-the-pitch-2263218.html \"Unsporting conduct on and off the pitch\"]. ''[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]''. Sunday, 18 July 2010.\n* O'Kelly, Emer. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/behaviour-that-brings-shame-upon-our-culture-2263219.html \"Behaviour that brings shame upon our 'culture'\"]. ''Sunday Independent''. Sunday, 18 July 2010.\n* [[Colm O'Rourke|O'Rourke, Colm]]. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/colm-orourke/colm-orourke-residue-of-bile-and-bitterness-could-easily-have-beenavoided-if-our-administrators-did-their-jobs-properly-2263255.html \"Residue of bile and bitterness could easily have beenavoided if our administrators did their jobs properly\"]. ''Sunday Independent''. Sunday, 18 July 2010.\n* Conlon, Tommy. [http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/louth-victims-of-another-fine-mess-from-the-most-amateur-of-amateur-organisations-2263256.html \"Louth victims of another fine mess from the most amateur of amateur organisations\"]. ''Sunday Independent''. Sunday, 18 July 2010.\n* [[Colm O'Rourke|O'Rourke, Colm]]. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/colm-orourke/colm-orourke-gilroys-charges-finding-their-stride-as-race-heats-up-2271742.html \"Gilroy's charges finding their stride as race heats up\"]. ''Sunday Independent''. Sunday, 25 July 2010.\n* Hayes, Liam. [http://www.tribune.ie/article/2010/aug/01/football-analyst-liam-hayes-kildare-and-meath-have/?q=louth_meath_leinster_final \"Kildare and Meath have a real chance to show credentials in white heat of battle\"]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''[[Sunday Tribune]]''. Sunday, 1 August 2010.\n* McKenna, Ewan. [http://www.tribune.ie/article/2010/aug/01/lilies-to-flower-in-battle-royal/?q=louth_meath_leinster_final \"Lilies to flower in battle Royal\"]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''Sunday Tribune''. Sunday, 1 August 2010.\n* [http://www.tribune.ie/article/2010/aug/01/lilies-to-flower-in-battle-royal/?q=louth_meath_leinster_final \"Diary of a... Meath forward\"]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''Sunday Tribune''. Sunday, 1 August 2010.\n* Shannon, Kieran. [http://www.tribune.ie/article/2010/aug/01/broken-treaty-are-limerick-the-unluckiest-team-of-/?q=louth_meath_leinster_final \"Broken Treaty \u2013 Are Limerick the unluckiest team of today?\"]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''Sunday Tribune''. Sunday, 1 August 2010.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120306035920/http://www.gaa.ie/gaa-news-and-videos/news-archive/1107101654-royals-late-show-breaks-wee-hearts/ Official GAA match report]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100714023000/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0711/gaa_championship_11_july_live_text.html As It Happened \u2013 Sunday's GAA Matches] \u2013 RT\u00c9's live text of the match\n* [http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/game-at-a-glance-2254832.html GAME AT A GLANCE] \u2013 Match statistics in the ''Irish Independent''\n* [http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/croke-park-chaos-2255911.html Croke Park chaos] \u2013 Timeline of controversy in the ''Irish Independent''\n\n{{Leinster Senior Football Championship}}\n\n[[Category:2010 in Gaelic football|Leinster Senior Football Championship Final]]\n[[Category:Brawls in team sports]]\n[[Category:Gaelic games controversies]]\n[[Category:Leinster Senior Football Championship Finals]]\n[[Category:Louth GAA matches]]\n[[Category:Meath GAA matches]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Irish English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox football match\n|                   title = 2010 Leinster Football Final\n|                   image = \n|                   event = [[Leinster Senior Football Championship]]\n|                   team1 = [[Louth GAA|Louth]]\n|        team1association = [[File:Cork colours.PNG|40px]]\n|              team1score = 1\u201310\n|                   team2 = [[Meath GAA|Meath]]\n|        team2association = [[File:Donegal colours.jpg|40px]]\n|              team2score = 1\u201312\n|                 details =\n|                    date = 11 July 2010\n|                 stadium = [[Croke Park]]\n|                    city = [[Dublin]]\n|      man_of_the_match1a =\n|                 referee = [[Martin Sludden]] ([[Tyrone GAA|Tyrone]])\n|              attendance = 48,875<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/><ref name=\"GAME AT A GLANCE\"/>\n|                 weather =\n|                previous = [[2009 Leinster Senior Football Championship Final|2009]]\n|                    next = [[2011 Leinster Senior Football Championship Final|2011]]\n}}\nThe '''2010 Leinster Senior Football Championship Final''' was the last [[Gaelic football|football]] match of the 2010 [[Leinster Senior Football Championship]], played between [[Louth GAA|Louth]] and [[Meath GAA|Meath]] on 11 July 2010 in [[Croke Park]], Dublin.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0707/1224274220413.html|title=GAA \u2013 weekly fixtures|date=7 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=7 July 2010}}</ref> Louth were appearing in their first Leinster Senior Football Championship Final in 50 years. The game is memorable for its contentious conclusion, such that in 2020 it was described as \"the most controversial Leinster final ever\".<ref name=\"10 years later\"/>\n\nMeath won by 1\u201312 to 1\u201310, thanks to a controversial late goal by [[Joe Sheridan (Gaelic footballer)|Joe Sheridan]]. The goal was deemed illegal by television replays but was declared valid by referee Martin Sludden, from [[County Tyrone]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/8808677.stm|title=Referee Martin Sludden struck after Leinster decider|date=11 July 2010|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=11 July 2010}}</ref> He then blew the final whistle. Irate Louth fans stormed the [[Football pitch|pitch]] and commenced a process of chasing and physically assaulting the referee, who had to be led away by a [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na|Garda]] escort in scenes broadcast to a live television audience. Other scenes of violence saw bottles being hurled from a stand, one striking a steward who fell to the ground. The situation led to much media debate in the week that followed, the violence was condemned by senior politicians (some of whom were in the stadium), and there were calls for the game to be replayed\u2014though, ultimately, this did not happen.\n\nSe\u00e1n Moran of ''[[The Irish Times]]'' said the next day: \"What will be most vividly remembered of the 2010 final was compressed into a minute at the very end of the match with Louth getting ready to celebrate a deserved win \u2013 first over their neighbours in 35 years \u2013 and a resilient display\".<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\">{{cite news|author=Moran, Se\u00e1n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0712/1224274518802.html|title=Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> Colm Keys of the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' said it was \"hard to disagree\" that it was \"the greatest injustice for many a year in Croke Park\",<ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/sheridans-cruel-twist-denies-louth-2254831.html|title=Sheridan's cruel twist denies Louth|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> and remarked: \"The 320th anniversary of the [[Battle of the Boyne]] is being commemorated today, but that surely didn't throw up a talking point to match a Joe Sheridan goal that will have the counties divided by [[River Boyne|the same river]] at odds for years to come\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/fitzpatrick-slams-disgraceful-decision-2254830.html|title=Fitzpatrick slams 'disgraceful decision'|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==History of rivalry==\nLouth and Meath were rivals of old, both winning the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] in the 1950s; however, this was to be Louth's first appearance in the Leinster Senior Football Championship Final since a 1960 to [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]].<ref name=\"Meath will look to win midfield battle\">{{cite news|author=Moran, Se\u00e1n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0710/1224274420582.html|title=Meath will look to win midfield battle|date=10 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=10 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Border dispute with wee bit of history\"/> According to [[Colm O'Rourke]], \"there was a time in the late 1940s and '50s when Meath and Louth were the two best teams in the province [of Leinster] and played some memorable championship games\".<ref>{{cite news|author=O'Rourke, Colm|author-link=Colm O'Rourke|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/colm-orourke/colm-orourke-great-rivals-of-the-dim-and-distant-past-are-reunitedbut-louths-fairytale-day-wont-have-a-happy-ending-2254156.html|title=Great rivals of the dim and distant past are reunitedbut Louth's fairytale day won't have a happy ending|date=11 July 2010|work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=11 July 2010}}</ref> Keith Duggan of ''The Irish Times'' reported that the two teams \"fight like alley cats\".<ref name=\"Border dispute with wee bit of history\">{{cite news|author=Duggan, Keith|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0710/1224274420598.html|title=Border dispute with wee bit of history|date=10 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=10 July 2010}}</ref> They had last met four years previously in a preliminary round of the Leinster Senior Football Championship, with Meath emerging victorious.<ref name=\"Meath will look to win midfield battle\"/> Louth had last defeated Meath in 1975, also at Croke Park.<ref name=\"Meath will look to win midfield battle\"/> Three matches were required to produce a winner when the two encountered each other in July 1949.<ref name=\"Border dispute with wee bit of history\"/> Other meetings include a draw in a semi-final of the 1951 Leinster Senior Football Championship, with Meath narrowly winning the replay.<ref name=\"Border dispute with wee bit of history\"/> Meath also defeated Louth in the 1952 Leinster Senior Football Championship Final.<ref name=\"Border dispute with wee bit of history\"/> Following on from Louth's aforementioned 1975 victory, there were other Meath wins in 1998, 2002 and 2006.<ref name=\"Border dispute with wee bit of history\"/>\n\n==Route to the final==\n'''Preliminary Round:''' Louth 1\u201311 [[Longford GAA|Longford]] 1\u20137; Meath 1\u201320 Offaly 2\u20137<br />\n'''Quarter-finals:''' Louth 1\u201322 [[Kildare GAA|Kildare]] 1\u201316; Meath 2\u201314 [[Laois GAA|Laois]] 0\u201310<br />\n'''Semi-finals:''' Louth 1\u201315 [[Westmeath GAA|Westmeath]] 2\u201310; Meath 5\u20139 [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] 0\u201313\n\n==Pre-match==\n\n===Team selection===\nOn 9 July, both teams announced their teams for the final.<ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0709/1224274348043.html|title=Kenny resumes his position in central role|date=9 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=9 July 2010|quote=Both Meath and Louth will today release their starting line-ups for Sunday's Leinster football final in Croke Park \u2013 and while Louth are likely to be unchanged from their semi-final win over Westmeath, Meath are expected to start Nigel Crawford at midfield, the only likely switch from the team which ripped Dublin apart in their semi-final.}}</ref> Meath announced their team first, with captain [[Nigel Crawford]], returning after injury, replacing [[Mark Ward (Meath GAA footballer born 1985)|Mark Ward]] in midfield.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0709/1224274378545.html|title=Crawford to start against Louth|date=9 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=9 July 2010|quote=Nigel Crawford comes into the Meath midfield for Sunday's Leinster final against Louth. Crawford, who has fully recovered from a back injury, will start alongside Brian Meade in the Meath engine room with Mark Ward making way. Louth manager Peter Fitzpatrick will announce his team later today.}}</ref>\n\n===Attendance===\nIt was anticipated beforehand that attendance would be at its lowest of the decade, estimated at 45,000 or 50,000 by Ian O'Riordan of ''The Irish Times''.<ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0709/1224274348000.html|title=Lowest crowd in decade due for final|date=9 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=9 July 2010}}</ref> 48,875 people attended the game.<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/><ref name=\"GAME AT A GLANCE\"/> The issue of applying fencing around Croke Park to prevent pitch invasions had been discussed prior to the game.<ref>{{cite news|author=Moran, Se\u00e1n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0706/1224274102516.html|title=McKenna reiterates warning on fencing|date=6 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=6 July 2010|quote=Last Sunday, saw Kilkenny retain their provincial title against Galway without problems but a county winning a sixth successive provincial title is unlike to spark the same reaction as next weekend when Meath, for the first time in nine years, or Louth, for the first time in 50, will raise the Leinster football trophy.}}</ref> The violent scenes which followed the 2010 Leinster Senior Football Championship Final renewed this debate in the days afterwards,<ref name=\"Referee admits error in awarding Meath goal\"/><ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0713/1224274590265.html|title=GAA say fencing would be last resort|date=13 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> though President Cooney later said \"the last thing we want to do is put fencing up around Croke Park\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0720/cooneyc.html |title=Cooney confirms pitch presentations |date=20 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=20 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722063726/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0720/cooneyc.html |archivedate=22 July 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0720/1224275100231.html|title=GAA plans for on-pitch presentations|date=20 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=20 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\nLouth's [[JP Rooney]] and [[Shane Lennon]] both missed opportunities in the first half.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0711/1224274490689.html|title=Rough justice for heartbroken Louth|date=11 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=11 July 2010}}</ref> Louth dominated the second half, though spurned numerous opportunities to take a commanding lead over Meath.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> Rooney scored a goal with seven minutes of the game left.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> Meath converted two long-range free kicks from [[Cian Ward]], but Louth still led by one point in the final minute.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> Louth's [[Colm Judge]] was sent off in the 69th minute for a second bookable offence.<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/><ref name=\"GAME AT A GLANCE\"/> Then came the controversial goal by [[Joe Sheridan (Gaelic footballer)|Joe Sheridan]] in the third minute of stoppage time.<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/> The ball was kicked into the square by Graham Reilly. It came out to [[Seamus Kenny (footballer)|Seamus Kenny]], who could have gone for the point, but saw a goal chance and shot. But the ball was blocked by Louth captain [[Paddy Keenan]], and fell into the square, towards Louth full-back [[Dessie Finnegan]]. But Finnegan failed to clear and the ball went straight to Joe Sheridan, who fell over the goal line and then threw the ball into the net \u2013 both illegal moves.<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/> Sheridan was also \"inside the square\" at the time the ball reached him, in a third illegal move. Yet the goal was allowed and all of a sudden Meath were winning by two points.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> Referee Sludden checked with the umpire and did not change his mind,<ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/> blowing his whistle for full-time soon after with the score at Meath 1\u201312: Louth 1\u201310, much to the disappointment of everyone associated with Louth.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> TV replays immediately demonstrated that the referee was incorrect when he awarded the goal to Meath.<ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/>\n\n===Violence===\nLouth fans poured onto the pitch to express their feelings to the referee,<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/><ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/> and, in the words of ''The Irish Times'', \"all hell broke loose\".<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> At least four fans physically attacked Sludden and struck him with violence.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/><ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/><ref name=\"Dark clouds cast over Louth's big day in the sun\"/> One man who was wearing a red shirt shoved Sludden in the chest before being pursued by television cameras as he made his departure.<ref>{{cite news|author1=McGarry, Patsy  |author2=Lally, Conor|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/0712/1224274518490.html|title=Referee shoved in chest after GAA final|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010|quote=THERE WERE no arrests in Croke Park yesterday despite unruly scenes at the end of the Leinster football final between Louth and Meath in which referee Martin Sludden was pushed and jostled. [...] A man in a red shirt rushed onto the field and shoved the referee in the chest. He was followed by RT\u00c9 cameras as he left the scene.}}</ref> Sludden was awarded a [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na|Garda]] escort as he made haste his escape from the pitch.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/><ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/> Stadium director Peter McKenna said the referee was \"very shaken\" after his experience.<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/>\n\nLouth manager [[Peter Fitzpatrick]] intervened to physically urge the fans to halt their behaviour,<ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0711/crokerpark_meath_louth.html |title=Referee is attacked in Croke Park |date=11 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=11 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100712234014/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0711/crokerpark_meath_louth.html |archivedate=12 July 2010 }}</ref> an act later described by the ''Irish Independent'' as \"a remarkable display of composure from the [[Dundalk]] man, who had every right to be spitting feathers at the defeat\".<ref name=\"Bookies' handout eases Louth pain\"/> Meath substitute [[Mark Ward (Meath GAA footballer born 1985)|Mark Ward]] was hit by a Louth fan.<ref name=\"10 Key questions after Sunday's chaotic scenes at Croker\"/> Children cried and looked sad, and one child allegedly received a wound when hit by a steward.<ref name=\"Gardai close in on Croker prosecutions\"/> Bottles were hurled from the stands.<ref name=\"Dark clouds cast over Louth's big day in the sun\"/> A steward also received wounds when he was assaulted by a soft drinks bottle.<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/><ref name=\"Meath call for extra time over Louth replay bid\"/> He was given medical attention,<ref name=\"Dark clouds cast over Louth's big day in the sun\"/> and later declared fit to steward further matches.<ref name=\"Meath call for extra time over Louth replay bid\"/>\n\nElsewhere in the stadium, former Meath All-Ireland Senior Football Championship-winning manager [[Se\u00e1n Boylan]] was involved in an altercation with an irate Louth fan in a corporate box.<ref name=\"Boylan plays down incident with Louth fan\">{{cite news|author=McHale, Michael|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/boylan-plays-down-incident-with-louth-fan-2254940.html|title=Boylan plays down incident with Louth fan|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Boylan plays down incident with Louth fan\"/> Boylan said: \"People lose the head all the time\" and that he was \"more embarrassed than anything\".<ref name=\"Boylan plays down incident with Louth fan\"/>\n\n===Details===\n{{football box\n|date=11 July 2010\n|time = 14:00 [[Irish Summer Time|UTC+1]]\n|team1 = [[Louth GAA|Louth]]\n|score = 1\u201310 \u2013 1\u201312\n|report = [http://www.gaa.ie/gaa-news-and-videos/news-archive/1107101654-royals-late-show-breaks-wee-hearts/ (Report)]\n|team2 = [[Meath GAA|Meath]]\n|goals1 = P Keenan (0-1), B White (0-4, 3f), A McDonnell (0-1), A Reed (0-1), C Judge (0-2, 1f), JP Rooney (1-1)\n|goals2 =  A Moyles (0-1), N Crawford (0-1), J Sheridan (1-0), G Reilly (0-4), C Ward (0-4, 4f), S Bray (0-2)\n|stadium = [[Croke Park]], Dublin\n|attendance = 48,875<ref name=\"Controversy abounds as Meath claim title in hectic final minutes\"/><ref name=\"GAME AT A GLANCE\"/>\n|referee = [[Martin Sludden]]\n}}\n\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = _whiteshoulders\n |pattern_b  = _thinwhitesides\n |pattern_ra = _whiteshoulders\n |leftarm    = ff0000\n |body       = ff0000\n |rightarm   = ff0000\n |shorts     = FFFFFF\n |socks      = ff0000\n |title      = Louth\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = yellowshoulders\n |pattern_b  = _thinyellowsides\n |pattern_ra = _yellowshoulders\n |leftarm    = 28AE7B\n |body       = 28AE7B\n |rightarm   = 28AE7B\n |shorts     = FFFFFF\n |socks      = 28AE7B\n |title      = Meath\n}}\n|}\n\n==View of match participants==\n\n===Joe Sheridan===\nJoe Sheridan, who scored the controversial goal, described how he had done it: \"It was well-worked and it was a definite goal. People are saying I threw it in, but I was heading for the line and I just dropped the ball and it was in the net. I got it and the lad just pushed me into the net. I tried to do whatever I could to hit it and the goal was given, simple as that. I was pushed in over the line so it should have been a penalty anyway. I think it was a perfect goal\".<ref name=\"Little sympathy in Meath camp\"/>\n\n===Match officials===\nReferee Martin Sludden later admitted he had made an error.<ref name=\"Referee admits error in awarding Meath goal\"/><ref name=\"10 Key questions after Sunday's chaotic scenes at Croker\"/> His referee's report acknowledged a \"terrible mistake\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0715/1224274738230.html|title=Louth move on but sense of injustice persists|date=15 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=15 July 2010|quote=In the light of this and the clear admission in the referee's report that he \"made a terrible mistake\", the referee's report therefore is questionable. [...] We would contend that the committee/ council in charge erred in leaving the matter to Meath County Board to offer a replay, without seeking clarification from the referee in relation to his match report and his statement \"he made a terrible mistake\".}}</ref> However, based on past refereeing errors, his place on the panel of 18 referees to officiate during the 2010 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship was secure, though the likelihood of him refereeing another match was less so.<ref name=\"10 Key questions after Sunday's chaotic scenes at Croker\">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/10-key-questions-after-sundays-chaotic-scenes-at-croker-2255907.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130111155028/http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/10-key-questions-after-sundays-chaotic-scenes-at-croker-2255907.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 January 2013 |title=10 Key questions after Sunday's chaotic scenes at Croker |date=13 July 2010 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 }}</ref> It was thought likely he had been deducted four points from one hundred for his error by his assessor (1 for missing a foul and 3 for Meath profiting from it with a score), though rules banning the assessor from looking at video evidence meant Sludden may not have been deducted any points if the assessor could not see the incident properly from the stand.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Kelly, Liam  |author2=Foley, Cliona|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/bullish-gilroy-unrepentant-after-depriving-daly-of-dual-star-ocarroll-2262636.html|title=Bullish Gilroy unrepentant after depriving Daly of dual star O'Carroll|date=17 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=17 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Team managers===\nLouth manager Peter Fitzpatrick said he was \"absolutely devastated\" on RT\u00c9.<ref name=\"Meath county board asks for more time\"/> Appearing later on radio station [[LMFM]], he described the referee as \"[[Dick Turpin]] without a mask\", adding \"It was pure daylight robbery. I'm very, very annoyed\".<ref name=\"Little sympathy in Meath camp\"/>\n\nWhen questioned at a press conference about Sheridan's goal, Meath manager Eamon O'Brien said: \"I can't say and I'm not commenting. I can comment, as I said to RT\u00c9, that loads of decisions were made during the game that didn't go our way. I can recall three or four balls that were blown for picking off the ground that I didn\u2019t think were off the ground. Nigel Crawford was booked up here and Louth got a point off it. The game goes for 70 minutes, decisions are made and you live with it. That\u2019s it, that\u2019s the way I see it\".<ref name=\"Little sympathy in Meath camp\"/>\n\n===Other players===\nMeath's captain Nigel Crawford gave his opinion on the incident: \"I'm sure most players have been involved in controversial situations like that where you get calls for replays and things like that happening, but I just don't think it's possible or I just don't think it can happen. If you start that, where do you end up? Do we go back and say the ball wasn\u2019t on the ground when we touched it and they got a free or whatever? It's just very unfortunate that it happens in a high-profile game right at the end of a game to a team that hasn't won in a long time. It's just a very unfortunate situation\".<ref name=\"Little sympathy in Meath camp\"/>\n\nLouth player J. P. Rooney said: \"Aaron Hoey was pleading with [Sludden] to consult with his umpires but when he went in, he told them to put up the green flag. [...] I know it's wrong, people running at the ref, but you can see why Louth people did it. He brought it on himself and I wouldn't feel sorry for him\".<ref name=\"Who said what . . .\"/>\n\n==Reaction==\n\n===Media===\nThe ''Irish Independent'' said \"Meath's Leinster Final goal-that-never-was will go down in history \u2013 and not only in Ireland, since by now the images have flashed round the world \u2013 among the great injustices suffered in any sport\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/editorial/gaa-must-play-fair-by-louth-2255101.html|title=GAA must play fair by Louth|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> ''The Irish Times'' described \"ugly scenes\",<ref name=\"Rough justice for heartbroken Louth\"/> with Damian Cullen calling it \"one of the strangest endings ever to a GAA match\",<ref name=\"September Road\"/> Se\u00e1n Moran describing it as \"the most extraordinary refereeing error since Jimmy Cooney whistled up early 12 years ago\",<ref name=\"Little sympathy in Meath camp\">{{cite news|author=Moran, Se\u00e1n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0712/1224274518857.html|title=Little sympathy in Meath camp|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> and the newspaper publishing numerous letters on the topic from disgruntled members of the public every day that week.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/letters/2010/0713/1224274589427.html|title=Controversy over Leinster final|date=13 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/letters/2010/0714/1224274657571.html|title=Controversy over Leinster final|date=14 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/letters/2010/0715/1224274739007.html|title=Controversy over Leinster final|date=15 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/letters/2010/0716/1224274821598.html|title=Controversy over Leinster final|date=16 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=16 July 2010}}</ref> The same newspaper's Philip Reid remarked upon the coincidence that these events had occurred on the same day as the [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final]] in South Africa, wondered why goal-line technology could not be used and added: \"On this point, it would appear, the GAA and [[FIFA]] have something in common: they live in the times of the dinosaur\".<ref name=\"Dark clouds cast over Louth's big day in the sun\">{{cite news|author=Reid, Philip|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0712/1224274518576.html|title=Dark clouds cast over Louth's big day in the sun|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> The events in Croke Park led to less prominent newspaper coverage of the FIFA World Cup Final itself the next day.<ref name=\"10 Key questions after Sunday's chaotic scenes at Croker\"/> The incident surrounding the goal was likened to [[Thierry Henry]]'s illegal handball in the [[2009 Republic of Ireland vs France football matches|France vs Republic of Ireland 2010 FIFA World Cup play-off]].<ref name=\"September Road\">{{cite news|author=Cullen, Damian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0712/1224274518850.html|title=September Road|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010|quote=AFTER Joe \"Thierry Henry\" Sheridan's controversial handling of the ball at the end of yesterday's Leinster final, we wracked our brains for some of the other controversial and bizarre endings to GAA matches.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Watterson, Johnny|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0717/1224274900960.html|title=Hold the back page|date=17 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=17 July 2010|quote=The unravelling of the Leinster football final sparked off radical suggestions the match should be replayed and while not as globally embarrassing as the FAI whimpering over the Thierry Henry hand ball, it seemed equally absurd. While Meath diplomacy forbids them to ridicule the \"Replayistas\" in the manner Fifa boss Sepp Blatter did with the FAI, be sure Meath players bridled at the suggestion.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Bray, Allison  |author2=Keys, Colm  |author3=Clarke, Denise  |last-author-amp=yes|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/mayhem-and-madness-as-fans-attack-referee-2254900.html|title=Mayhem and madness as fans attack referee|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010|quote=Meath chairman Barney Allen refused to be drawn on a potential offer of a replay afterwards, drawing comparison with the Irish soccer team's plight last November after the Thierry Henry handball. \"Ireland didn't get a replay when France got a lucky goal,\" said Mr Allen.}}</ref> Public service broadcaster RT\u00c9 referred to \"disgraceful scenes\".<ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/> The GAA website's official match report brushed aside the controversy, saying Sheridan had \"smuggled the ball over the line\".<ref name=\"September Road\"/> [[Eugene McGee]], writing in the ''Irish Independent'', said \"It will be a stain on the good name of the GAA if this result is allowed to stand\".<ref>{{cite news|author=McGee, Eugene|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/eugene-mcgee/eugene-mcgee-if-fair-play-exists-in-the-gaa-louth-should-get-their-replay-2254833.html|title=If fair play exists in the gaa, Louth should get their replay|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> His colleague [[Martin Breheny]] said there ought to be no replay and that \"no sport can run its affairs on the basis of sentiment\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Breheny, Martin|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/we-cant-replay-gaa-has-no-room-for-sentiment-2257325.html|title=We can't replay \u2013 GAA has no room for sentiment|date=14 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===GAA administrators===\nThe following day, the GAA released a statement confirming that Sludden admitted he had made an error.<ref name=\"Referee admits error in awarding Meath goal\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0712/meath_louth1.html |title=Referee admits error in awarding Meath goal |date=12 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=12 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714155354/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0712/meath_louth1.html |archivedate=14 July 2010 }}</ref> The GAA also stated that the rules left it powerless to offer a replay and that this would be decided by Meath,<ref name=\"Referee admits error in awarding Meath goal\"/><ref name=\"10 Key questions after Sunday's chaotic scenes at Croker\"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Moran, Se\u00e1n|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0712/1224274518866.html|title=Replay only possible if Royal offer is made|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> though most Meath players did not wish to facilitate a replay,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0713/meath_louth.html |title=Royals reluctant to offer Louth replay |date=13 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714155404/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0713/meath_louth.html |archivedate=14 July 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/8812395.stm|title=Louth hopes of replay fade after Meath players say 'no'|date=13 July 2010|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> while former Meath players were said to be in favour of one.<ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/meath-buy-time-2256002.html|title=Meath buy time. . . but players and management likely to put an end to Louth's replay hopes|date=13 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> The GAA said it would work with the authorities to capture Sludden's attackers.<ref name=\"Referee admits error in awarding Meath goal\"/>\n\n[[List of Presidents of the Gaelic Athletic Association|GAA President]] [[Christy Cooney]] said the events were a \"watershed\" and one where the \"circumstances were bizarre. I have never seen circumstances like it as long as I have been a member of this Association\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0716/cooney.html |title=Cooney \u2013 Leinster final a watershed for GAA |date=16 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=16 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717195114/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0716/cooney.html |archivedate=17 July 2010 }}</ref> He promised life bans for those who assaulted the referee.<ref>{{cite news|author=Foley, Cliona |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/we-will-impose-life-bans-cooney-2262817.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802073852/http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/we-will-impose-life-bans-cooney-2262817.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 2 August 2012 |title=We will impose life bans: Cooney |date=17 July 2010 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |accessdate=17 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nCroke Park's stadium director Peter McKenna questioned why Louth manager Peter Fitzpatrick had walked onto the pitch to ask the referee about the decision.<ref name=\"Dark clouds cast over Louth's big day in the sun\"/> [[Gaelic Players Association]] (GPA) chief executive [[Dessie Farrell]] said: \"What went on last Sunday was a PR disaster for us all\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/louth-facing-decision-on-use-of-navan-as-home-venue-2260931.html|title=Louth facing decision on use of Navan as 'home' venue|date=16 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=16 July 2010}}</ref> The National Referees Committee gave a negative response to the idea of goal-line technology being used in future.<ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0713/1224274590243.html|title=Referees in no rush for video technology|date=13 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> Retired referee [[John Bannon (referee)|John Bannon]] said \"No one deserves to be attacked, either verbally or physically, especially in Croke Park. [...] This attitude still remains part of the GAA's culture, it has never been rooted out\".<ref name=\"Who said what . . .\">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/who-said-what-2255909.html|title=Who said what . . .|date=13 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> [[Tyrone GAA|Tyrone]] County Board (from where the referee originated) sympathised with the Sludden but said the crowd's reaction was \"unbelievable\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Cahill, Jackie|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/red-hand-chairman-standing-by-underfire-ref-sludden-2259098.html|title=Red Hand chairman standing by under-fire ref Sludden|date=15 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> [[Liam O'Neill]], a candidate for the GAA presidency in 2012, later said: \"Quite simply, there should have been a re-fixture for that game. Everyone knows that. Everyone knows a wrong was perpetrated\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Cummiskey, Gavin|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0721/1224275144935.html|title=O'Neill calls for change to five-year term on playing laws|date=21 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=21 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===GAA personalities===\nThere was significant public and analytical support for Louth and condemnation of the refereeing decision.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0712/meath_louth.html |title=Massive support for Wee County |date=12 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=12 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714155349/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0712/meath_louth.html |archivedate=14 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn ''[[The Sunday Game]]'' TV highlights programme, [[Pat Spillane]] called both the fans and the referee \"disgraceful\", commenting: {{cquote|Those were disgraceful scenes at the end. Cowardly individuals attacking a referee who is doing it in a voluntary capacity. There is no place in the GAA for people like that. Scandalous scenes and a bad day for the GAA on that account. A fella doing a job made a human error. He made a mistake. We cannot condone those scenes, they are disgraceful and punishments must be handed out. However, just as disgraceful is that Louth were robbed of their first Leinster title since 1957 by a complete refereeing mistake. Joe Sheridan threw the ball over the line. Under any rules of the game, experimental or not, the goal should not have been allowed.<ref name=\"Referee is attacked in Croke Park\"/>}}\n\nFormer Meath player [[Trevor Giles]] said: \"If this victory stands, it won't do Meath any favours because there will always be a question mark over the result\".<ref name=\"Who said what . . .\"/> Former [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] footballer [[Darragh \u00d3 S\u00e9]] described the idea of Meath County Board having the final decision on a replay as \"a complete and utter cop-out\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0714/1224274657319.html|title=Controversies highlight that the GAA must start to show some direction|date=14 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref> Former Kerry footballer and manager [[P\u00e1id\u00ed \u00d3 S\u00e9]] said: \"there is no way any referee should have allowed Sheridan's goal to stand\".<ref>{{cite news|author=\u00d3 S\u00e9, P\u00e1id\u00ed|author-link=P\u00e1id\u00ed \u00d3 S\u00e9|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/in-sport-you-have-to-take-the-rough-with-the-smooth-2263257.html|title=In sport, you have to take the rough with the smooth|date=18 July 2010|work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=18 July 2010}}</ref> [[Sligo GAA|Sligo]] footballer [[Eamonn O'Hara]] suggested that the events gave \"the perfect opportunity [for the GAA] to revamp the way match-day officials are selected\".<ref>{{cite news|author=O'Hara, Eamonn|author-link=Eamonn O'Hara|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/leinster-final-chaos-presents-perfect-chance-to-revamp-umpire-selection-2263884.html|title=Leinster final chaos presents perfect chance to revamp umpire selection|date=19 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nVeteran commentator [[M\u00edche\u00e1l \u00d3 Muircheartaigh]] told [[Ryan Tubridy]] on [[The Tubridy Show|his radio show]] that \"Croke Park abdicated responsibility. They should have taken the matter from Meath\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Keane, Billy|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/gaarsquos-abdication-of-responsibility-towards-royals-has-tarnished-their-leinster-crown-2262810.html|title=GAA's abdication of responsibility towards Royals has tarnished their Leinster crown|date=17 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=17 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Politicians===\n[[Minister for Justice and Equality|Minister for Justice and Law Reform]] [[Dermot Ahern]], himself from Louth, made known his condemnation of the violence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.examiner.ie/breakingnews/ireland/justice-minister-condemns-altercations-at-gaa-game-465189.html|title=Justice Minister condemns altercations at GAA game|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|publisher=[[Thomas Crosbie Holdings]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> He attended the match.<ref name=\"Ahern deplores Croke Park scenes\">{{cite news|author1=Parsons, Michael  |author2=Minihan, Mary|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/0713/1224274589396.html|title=Ahern deplores Croke Park scenes|date=13 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> [[Taoiseach]] [[Brian Cowen]] also made known his disapproval later from New York: \"I didn't see what happened as the ref was leaving the pitch. But obviously none of that is justified. It was an exciting match obviously. But it doesn't justify anyone engaging in that sort of activity. So I wouldn't like to see it repeated anywhere\".<ref name=\"Ahern deplores Croke Park scenes\"/> Cowen was also at the match.<ref name=\"Ahern deplores Croke Park scenes\"/>\n\n===Other===\nThe [[Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na]] announced that it would investigate those persons they said breached the Non-fatal Offences Against the Person Act by battering the referee and others.<ref name=\"Gardai close in on Croker prosecutions\">{{cite news|author1=Cusack, Jim  |author2=Lawlor, Damian|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/gardai-close-in-on-croker-prosecutions-2263264.html|title=Garda\u00ed close in on Croker prosecutions|date=18 July 2010|work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=18 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nBookmaker [[Boylesports]] paid all losing bets on the match.<ref name=\"Bookies' handout eases Louth pain\">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/bookies-handout-eases-louth-pain-2254846.html|title=Bookies' handout eases Louth pain|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Outcome==\nOn 13 July, Louth's county executive committee issued a statement condemning what it described as \"the unsavoury incidents after the match\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0713/louth_meath.html |title=Louth condemn Croke Park attack |date=13 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714155359/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0713/louth_meath.html |archivedate=14 July 2010 }}</ref> Meath's county board gathered in [[Navan]] but did not issue an immediate statement, instead requesting more time to think.<ref name=\"Meath call for extra time over Louth replay bid\">{{cite news|author1=Keys, Colm |author2=McHale, Michael |url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/meath-call-for-extra-time-over-louth-replay-bid-2255978.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130108004530/http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/meath-call-for-extra-time-over-louth-replay-bid-2255978.html |url-status=dead |archive-date= 8 January 2013 |title=Meath call for extra time over Louth replay bid |date=13 July 2010 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |accessdate=13 July 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"Meath county board asks for more time\">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0712/1224274552634.html|title=Meath county board asks for more time|date=12 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0713/1224274590229.html|title=Meath's deferral of final decision makes chance of replay less likely|date=13 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> They later decided that there would be no replay, this would be \"the end of the matter\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0713/1224274613334.html|title=Meath decide against offering replay|date=13 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=13 July 2010}}</ref> Meath were officially champions of Leinster for 2010,<ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0714/1224274680949.html|title=Louth left to ponder options|date=14 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=14 July 2010|quote=In the end they delivered on the greater expectation that the result must, under GAA rule, still stand, and that, as far as they were concerned, \"was the end of the matter\". It means Meath go forward as Leinster football champions, in name at least.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0714/1224274660841.html|title=Meath rule out replay to leave Louth pondering options|date=14 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref> though Meath secretary Cyril Creavin conceded that it was a \"tainted\" title and that \"Some of the players are devastated with the reaction in newspapers\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/louths-legal-move-2257402.html|title=Louth's legal move|date=14 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/8820138.stm|title=Louth hopes of replay end as Meath board says 'no'|date=14 July 2010|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref> Louth accepted this: their official statement referred to the [[July 2010 R238 traffic collision]] which occurred on the same day as the final, sympathising with relatives of the eight people killed, and opting to avoid legal action in such a context.<ref name=\"Louth to take no further action\"/> Therefore, Meath automatically entered the quarter-finals of the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]], with Louth left to qualify for that same stage by playing (and winning) a further game in Round 4<ref name=\"GAME AT A GLANCE\">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/game-at-a-glance-2254832.html|title=GAME AT A GLANCE|date=12 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> of the All-Ireland qualifiers.<ref name=\"Louth to take no further action\">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0714/1224274728235.html|title=Louth to take no further action|date=14 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=14 July 2010|quote=\u201cFinally, in light of [[July 2010 R238 traffic collision|the tragic events which occurred in Donegal over the weekend]] we realise that we must put our situation in context and we would like to extend our deepest sympathies to the family and friends of those deceased.\"}}</ref>\n\nLouth were drawn against [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] in their next game.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0719/1224275061957.html|title=Louth get Croke Park date with Dublin|date=19 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0719/1224275033301.html|title=Louth draw qualifier date with Dublin|date=19 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=O'Riordan, Ian|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0719/1224275017767.html|title=Roscommon shine once again as Sligo can't live up to expectations|date=19 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=19 July 2010|quote=The big question about the Dublin-Louth pairing is how well Louth can recover from last Sunday's Leinster final fiasco against Meath, because unless they come out fighting again, Dublin have a great chance of making the All-Ireland quarter-final.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0721/1224275145109.html|title=Fitzpatrick delighted with 'dream' draw|date=21 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=21 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/louth-must-pick-up-pieces-as-resurgent-dublin-await-in-qualifiers-2263873.html|title=Louth must pick up pieces as resurgent Dublin await in qualifiers|date=19 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref> The appointment of experienced referee [[Pat McEnaney]] was scrutinised and praised in advance.<ref>{{cite news|author=Keys, Colm|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/mcenaney-to-take-charge-of-louthdublin-croker-clash-2265916.html|title=McEnaney to take charge of Louth-Dublin Croker clash|date=21 July 2010|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=21 July 2010|quote=McEnaney's appointment will be viewed as a secure option after the dramatic and tension-filled scenes at the end of the Leinster football final at the same venue 10 days ago.}}</ref> In the game, held once again at Croke Park on 24 July,<ref>{{cite news|author=Cummiskey, Gavin|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2010/0720/1224275073430.html|title=It's double headers back to back|date=20 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=20 July 2010|quote=The Dublin footballers, as expected and despite the low turnouts for their recent victories over Tipperary and Armagh, are back in Croke Park for a fifth time this season, and third successive week, as they attempt to salvage their campaign against Louth. That means the defeated Leinster finalists must return to the scene of the crime that saw referee Martin Sludden assaulted by supporters after the provincial decider against Meath on July 11th.}}</ref> Louth were defeated by 2\u201314 to 0\u201313, thus being eliminated from the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 2010|2010 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2010/0724/1224275433712.html|title=Dublin show no sympathy|date=24 July 2010|work=[[The Irish Times]]|publisher=Irish Times Trust|accessdate=24 July 2010|quote=Moral champions of Leinster they maybe but Louth are out of the All-Ireland football championship after being comprehensively beaten by Dublin at Croke Park. Two weeks after being denied a provincial title by a very bad call against Meath, the Wee County can have few complaints this time round.}}</ref><ref name=\"Dubs finally warming to summer task\">{{cite news|author=Crowe, Dermot|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/dubs-finally-warming-to-summer-task-2271850.html|title=Dubs finally warming to summer task|date=25 July 2010|work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|accessdate=25 July 2010|quote=Two weeks after they were stunned in the Leinster final, Louth still looked punch-drunk as the Dubs raced into an early lead, boosted by a goal from Eoghan O'Gara. They never recovered and the game limped to an inevitable conclusion. After the final whistle they went on a lap of honour to offer appreciation to their followers after the longest summer the county has witnessed in over half a century.}}</ref> By defeating Louth, Dublin joined Meath in the quarter-finals of the All-Ireland Senior Football Championship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0724/dublin_louth.html |title=Dublin 2\u201314 Louth 0\u201313 |date=24 July 2010 |work=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |accessdate=24 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724232452/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2010/0724/dublin_louth.html |archivedate=24 July 2010 }}</ref> For Louth so ended \"the longest summer the county has witnessed in over half a century\".<ref name=\"Dubs finally warming to summer task\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nLouth manager Fitzpatrick found success as a national politician; he was elected as a [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]] at the [[2011 Irish general election|2011 general election]] and re-elected several times after that.<ref name=\"10 years later\"/> He continued as Louth manager until after the 2012 season, at which point he left.<ref name=\"10 years later\"/>\n\nOn 15 September 2014, \"A Wee Royal Rumble - The Story of the 2010 Leinster Football Final\" was broadcast on [[RT\u00c9 One]] as part of ''[[Scannal]]'', the TV series dedicated to scandalous events.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hoganstand.com/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=224348|title=If it happened to Meath I'm sure the referee would have ended up in the canal|work=Hogan Stand|date=15 September 2014|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nNearly ten years later, in a newspaper article published on [[Easter|Easter Sunday]], Fitzpatrick - who had earlier watched the match for just the third time since (the first having been the night it was played) - stated that he had seen referee Sludden only once since: \"I went to [[Murder of Michaela McAreavey|Michaela Harte's funeral]] [in mid-January 2011] and he was ahead of me in the queue. That's the only time. I have never seen or{{sic}} spoken to him since\".<ref name=\"10 years later\">{{cite news|author=Crowe, Dermot|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/we-will-never-forget-the-11th-of-july-2010-peter-fitzpatrick-brian-white-and-joe-sheridan-reflect-on-a-day-that-shook-the-gaa-39103138.html|title='We will never forget the 11th of July 2010' - Peter Fitzpatrick, Brian White and Joe Sheridan reflect on a day that shook the GAA|date=5 April 2020|work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]|accessdate=5 April 2020|quote=A fortnight after the most controversial Leinster final ever, Kildare overpowered them [Meath].}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Vincent Hogan|Hogan, Vincent]]. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/vincent-hogan/vincent-hogan-sport-cant-force-social-values-it-reflects-them-2255842.html \"Sport can't force social values \u2013 it reflects them\"]. ''[[Irish Independent]]''. Tuesday, 13 July 2010.\n* Keys, Colm. [http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/the-fact-is-that-scenes-like-this-are-part-and-parcel-of-gaa-culture-2256001.html \"The fact is that scenes like this are part and parcel of GAA culture\"]. ''Irish Independent''. Tuesday, 13 July 2010.\n* Boyle, Donnchadh. [http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/leo-turley-2257320.html \"Leo Turley: Laois '95\"]. ''Irish Independent''. Wednesday, 14 July 2010.\n* Keys, Colm. [http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/the-great-hypocrisy-2257323.html \"The great hypocrisy\"]. ''Irish Independent''. Wednesday, 14 July 2010.\n* Devlin, Martina. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/martina-devlin/martina-devlin-stubborn-gaa-has-failed-its-referees-and-the-sport-2259059.html \"Stubborn GAA has failed its referees and the sport\"]. ''Irish Independent''. Thursday, 15 July 2010.\n* [[Martin Breheny|Breheny, Martin]]. [http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/net-gains-2259100.html \"Net gains\"]. ''Irish Independent''. Thursday, 15 July 2010.\n* Lynch, Declan. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/unsporting-conduct-on-and-off-the-pitch-2263218.html \"Unsporting conduct on and off the pitch\"]. ''[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]''. Sunday, 18 July 2010.\n* O'Kelly, Emer. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/behaviour-that-brings-shame-upon-our-culture-2263219.html \"Behaviour that brings shame upon our 'culture'\"]. ''Sunday Independent''. Sunday, 18 July 2010.\n* [[Colm O'Rourke|O'Rourke, Colm]]. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/colm-orourke/colm-orourke-residue-of-bile-and-bitterness-could-easily-have-beenavoided-if-our-administrators-did-their-jobs-properly-2263255.html \"Residue of bile and bitterness could easily have beenavoided if our administrators did their jobs properly\"]. ''Sunday Independent''. Sunday, 18 July 2010.\n* Conlon, Tommy. [http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/louth-victims-of-another-fine-mess-from-the-most-amateur-of-amateur-organisations-2263256.html \"Louth victims of another fine mess from the most amateur of amateur organisations\"]. ''Sunday Independent''. Sunday, 18 July 2010.\n* [[Colm O'Rourke|O'Rourke, Colm]]. [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/colm-orourke/colm-orourke-gilroys-charges-finding-their-stride-as-race-heats-up-2271742.html \"Gilroy's charges finding their stride as race heats up\"]. ''Sunday Independent''. Sunday, 25 July 2010.\n* Hayes, Liam. [http://www.tribune.ie/article/2010/aug/01/football-analyst-liam-hayes-kildare-and-meath-have/?q=louth_meath_leinster_final \"Kildare and Meath have a real chance to show credentials in white heat of battle\"]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''[[Sunday Tribune]]''. Sunday, 1 August 2010.\n* McKenna, Ewan. [http://www.tribune.ie/article/2010/aug/01/lilies-to-flower-in-battle-royal/?q=louth_meath_leinster_final \"Lilies to flower in battle Royal\"]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''Sunday Tribune''. Sunday, 1 August 2010.\n* [http://www.tribune.ie/article/2010/aug/01/lilies-to-flower-in-battle-royal/?q=louth_meath_leinster_final \"Diary of a... Meath forward\"]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''Sunday Tribune''. Sunday, 1 August 2010.\n* Shannon, Kieran. [http://www.tribune.ie/article/2010/aug/01/broken-treaty-are-limerick-the-unluckiest-team-of-/?q=louth_meath_leinster_final \"Broken Treaty \