{"title_page": "Lincoln International", "text_new": "{{about|the investment banking firm|the insurance and investment management company|Lincoln Financial}}{{Infobox company\n| name                = Lincoln International LLC\n| logo                = File:New_Lincoln_International_Logo.png\n| type                = [[Private company]]\n| parent              = \n| predecessor         = Lincoln Partners<br>Peters Associates\n| foundation          = 1996\n| founder             = [[Robert B. Barr]], Jim Lawson\n| location            = [[Chicago, Illinois]], [[United States]]\n| industry            = [[Investment banking]]\n| products            = [[Mergers & Acquisitions]], [[Fairness opinion]]s, [[Capital advisory]], [[Joint Ventures & Partnering]]\n| assets              = \n| homepage            = [http://www.lincolninternational.com www.lincolninternational.com]\n| num_employees       = 600+\n}}\n\n'''Lincoln International LLC''' is a multinational [[independent investment bank]] and [[financial services]] company specializing in advisory services and financings on [[Middle-market company|middle-market transactions]]. The firm works with publicly traded and privately owned companies, financial sponsors (private equity, venture capital, family offices, and hedge funds), and lenders.  The firm provides  advisory services including [[mergers & acquisitions]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lincolninternational.com/services/ma/|title=Mergers and Acquisitions {{!}} Global M&A Investment Banking|work=Lincoln International|access-date=2017-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref>, capital advisory<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lincolninternational.com/services/capital-advisory/|title=Capital Advisory}}</ref> consisting of growth equity<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lincolninternational.com/services/growth-equity/|title=Growth Equity}}</ref>, debt <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lincolninternational.com/services/debt-advisory/|title=Debt Advisory, Debt Counseling {{!}} International Debt Advisory|work=Lincoln International|access-date=2017-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref> and restructuring advisory<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lincolninternational.com/services/restructuring/|title=Restructuring}}</ref>, valuations and opinions<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lincolninternational.com/services/valuations-and-opinions/|title=Company Valuation Opinion {{!}} Independent Valuation Services|work=Lincoln International|access-date=2017-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref> and joint ventures & partnering<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lincolninternational.com/services/jv_partnering/|title=Joint Ventures & Partnering {{!}} Lincoln International|work=Lincoln International|access-date=2017-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref>. The firm completed more than 225 advisory assignments globally in 2019, as well as over 5,000 valuations.<ref>http://www.lincolninternational.com/en/about_us.html</ref>\n\nThe firm, which is headquartered in [[Chicago, Illinois]], was founded in 1996.  The company operates more than 20 offices in North America ([[Chicago]], [[Dallas]], [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City|New York]] and [[San Francisco]]), Europe ([[Amsterdam]], [[Brussels]], [[Frankfurt]], [[London]], [[Madrid]], [[Milan]], [[Moscow]], [[Munich]], [[Paris]], [[Stockholm]], [[Vienna]] and [[Zurich]]), Asia ([[Beijing]], [[Mumbai]], Bangalore and [[Tokyo]]) and South America ([[S\u00e3o Paulo]])\n\n==History==\nThe firm was founded by [https://www.lincolninternational.com/people/robert-barr/ Rob Barr] and [https://www.lincolninternational.com/people/lawrence-jim-lawson/ Jim Lawson], as well as [https://www.lincolninternational.com/people/edward-hanlon/ Ed Hanlon] and [https://www.lincolninternational.com/people/eric-malchow/ Eric Malchow], as a boutique investment banking firm, Lincoln Partners, in 1996. Barr and Lawson had worked together since 1981 and they began to work with Hanlon in 1988 and Malchow in 1994. Prior to founding Lincoln Partners, the partners spent most of their time working for [[Paine Webber]], which was acquired by UBS in 2000.\n\nThrough the late 1990s, Lincoln Partners grew to an organization of approximately 30 people and became a registered broker dealer.\n\nIn January 2006, Lincoln International was formed through the merger of Lincoln Partners and Peters Associates, two middle market investment banks based in the U.S. and Germany, respectively, as well as a team from KPMG joining to form a Paris office.<ref>[http://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/news.pl?id=19080 Lincoln Partners joins with German, French entities].  Crain's Chicago Business, Jan. 10, 2006</ref>  At the time of the merger, Lincoln International had offices in Chicago, Frankfurt, New York and Paris. The two firms had previously worked together through a strategic joint venture established in 2005.<ref>[http://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/news.pl?id=15873 Lincoln Partners teams up with firm].  Crain's Chicago Business, March 21, 2005</ref><ref>[http://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/article.pl?article_id=24257 Mid-cap banks team with pen pals overseas].  Crain's Chicago Business, August 29, 2005</ref>\n\nAs of April 2020, Lincoln International has over 600 employees and is eyeing an [[IPO]] in the near future.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Marek |first1=Lynne |title=This rising investment bank is eyeing an IPO |url=https://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20160813/ISSUE01/308139995/chicago-investment-bank-lincoln-international-eyes-an-ipo |website=Crain's Chicago Business |publisher=Crain Communication |accessdate=27 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* [http://www.allbusiness.com/banking-finance/financial-markets-investing/13032163-1.html Lincoln International Focuses On U.K. PE].  Investment Dealers Digest, May 15, 2009 \n* [http://pdf.lincolninternational.com/Media/BuyoutsAwardsArticle_foster.pdf While Others Shrunk,. Lincoln International Grew].  Reuters Buyouts\n* [http://www.iddmagazine.com/news/lincoln-international-turns-to-healthcare-201991-1.html Lincoln International Turns to Health Care].  IDD Magazine, January 19, 2010\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110716135926/http://media.www.themsj.com/media/storage/paper207/news/2003/02/10/DayInTheLife/Day-In.The.Life.Lincoln.Partners-365590.shtml Day in the Life: Lincoln Partners].  Monroe Street Journal (Stephen M. Ross School of Business) Feb 10, 2003\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lincolninternational.com Lincoln International] (company website)\n\n{{Investment banks}}\n\n[[Category:Investment banks]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1996]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the investment banking firm|the insurance and investment management company|Lincoln Financial}}{{Infobox company\n| name = Lincoln International LLC\n| logo = File:New_Lincoln_International_Logo.png\n| type = [[Private company]]\n| parent = \n| predecessor = Lincoln Partners<br>Peters Associates\n| foundation = 1996\n| founder = [[Robert B. Barr]], Jim Lawson\n| location = [[Chicago, Illinois]], [[United States]]\n| industry = [[Investment banking]]\n| products = [[Mergers & Acquisitions]], [[Fairness opinion]]s, [[Capital advisory]], [[Joint Ventures & Partnering]]\n| assets = \n| homepage = [http://www.lincolninternational.com www.lincolninternational.com]\n| num_employees = 500+\n}}\n\n'''Lincoln International LLC''' is a multinational [[independent investment bank]] and [[financial services]] company specializing in advisory services and financings on [[Middle-market company|middle-market transactions]]. The firm works with publicly traded and privately owned companies, financial sponsors (private equity, venture capital, family offices, and hedge funds), and lenders.  The firm provides  advisory services including [[mergers & acquisitions]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lincolninternational.com/services/ma/|title=Mergers and Acquisitions {{!}} Global M&A Investment Banking|work=Lincoln International|access-date=2017-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref>, capital advisory<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lincolninternational.com/services/capital-advisory/|title=Capital Advisory}}</ref> consisting of growth equity<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lincolninternational.com/services/growth-equity/|title=Growth Equity}}</ref>, debt <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lincolninternational.com/services/debt-advisory/|title=Debt Advisory, Debt Counseling {{!}} International Debt Advisory|work=Lincoln International|access-date=2017-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref> and restructuring advisory<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lincolninternational.com/services/restructuring/|title=Restructuring}}</ref>, valuations and opinions<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lincolninternational.com/services/valuations-and-opinions/|title=Company Valuation Opinion {{!}} Independent Valuation Services|work=Lincoln International|access-date=2017-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref> and joint ventures & partnering<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lincolninternational.com/services/jv_partnering/|title=Joint Ventures & Partnering {{!}} Lincoln International|work=Lincoln International|access-date=2017-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref>. The firm completed more than 225 advisory assignments globally in 2019, as well as over 5,000 valuations.<ref>http://www.lincolninternational.com/en/about_us.html</ref>\n\nThe firm, which is headquartered in [[Chicago, Illinois]], was founded in 1996.  The company operates more than 20 offices in North America ([[Chicago]], [[Dallas]], [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City|New York]] and [[San Francisco]]), Europe ([[Amsterdam]], [[Brussels]], [[Frankfurt]], [[London]], [[Madrid]], [[Milan]], [[Moscow]], [[Munich]], [[Paris]], [[Stockholm]], [[Vienna]] and [[Zurich]]), Asia ([[Beijing]], [[Mumbai]], Bangalore and [[Tokyo]]) and South America ([[S\u00e3o Paulo]])\n\n==History==\nThe firm was founded by [https://www.lincolninternational.com/people/robert-barr/ Rob Barr] and [https://www.lincolninternational.com/people/lawrence-jim-lawson/ Jim Lawson], as well as [https://www.lincolninternational.com/people/edward-hanlon/ Ed Hanlon] and [https://www.lincolninternational.com/people/eric-malchow/ Eric Malchow], as a boutique investment banking firm, Lincoln Partners, in 1996. Barr and Lawson had worked together since 1981 and they began to work with Hanlon in 1988 and Malchow in 1994. Prior to founding Lincoln Partners, the partners spent most of their time working for [[Paine Webber]], which was acquired by UBS in 2000.\n\nThrough the late 1990s, Lincoln Partners grew to an organization of approximately 30 people and became a registered broker dealer.\n\nIn January 2006, Lincoln International was formed through the merger of Lincoln Partners and Peters Associates, two middle market investment banks based in the U.S. and Germany, respectively, as well as a team from KPMG joining to form a Paris office.<ref>[http://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/news.pl?id=19080 Lincoln Partners joins with German, French entities].  Crain's Chicago Business, Jan. 10, 2006</ref>  At the time of the merger, Lincoln International had offices in Chicago, Frankfurt, New York and Paris. The two firms had previously worked together through a strategic joint venture established in 2005.<ref>[http://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/news.pl?id=15873 Lincoln Partners teams up with firm].  Crain's Chicago Business, March 21, 2005</ref><ref>[http://www.chicagobusiness.com/cgi-bin/article.pl?article_id=24257 Mid-cap banks team with pen pals overseas].  Crain's Chicago Business, August 29, 2005</ref>\n\nAs of April 2020, Lincoln International has over 600 employees and is eyeing an [[IPO]] in the near future.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Marek |first1=Lynne |title=This rising investment bank is eyeing an IPO |url=https://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20160813/ISSUE01/308139995/chicago-investment-bank-lincoln-international-eyes-an-ipo |website=Crain's Chicago Business |publisher=Crain Communication |accessdate=27 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* [http://www.allbusiness.com/banking-finance/financial-markets-investing/13032163-1.html Lincoln International Focuses On U.K. PE].  Investment Dealers Digest, May 15, 2009 \n* [http://pdf.lincolninternational.com/Media/BuyoutsAwardsArticle_foster.pdf While Others Shrunk,. Lincoln International Grew].  Reuters Buyouts\n* [http://www.iddmagazine.com/news/lincoln-international-turns-to-healthcare-201991-1.html Lincoln International Turns to Health Care].  IDD Magazine, January 19, 2010\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110716135926/http://media.www.themsj.com/media/storage/paper207/news/2003/02/10/DayInTheLife/Day-In.The.Life.Lincoln.Partners-365590.shtml Day in the Life: Lincoln Partners].  Monroe Street Journal (Stephen M. Ross School of Business) Feb 10, 2003\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lincolninternational.com Lincoln International] (company website)\n\n{{Investment banks}}\n\n[[Category:Investment banks]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1996]]\n", "name_user": "Hab10213", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated number of employees", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lincoln_International"}
{"title_page": "Gary Tomlinson", "text_new": "'''Gary Alfred Tomlinson''' (born December 4, 1951) is an American [[musicologist]] and the John Hay Whitney Professor of Music and Humanities at [[Yale University]]. He was formerly the Annenberg Professor in the Humanities at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sas.upenn.edu/music/faculty/history.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-04-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100402075218/http://www.sas.upenn.edu/music/faculty/history.html |archive-date=2010-04-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He graduated from the [[University of California, Berkeley]], with a Ph.D., in 1979 with thesis titled ''Rinuccini, Peri, Monteverdi, and the humanist heritage of opera''.\n\nTomlinson became Director of the Whitney Humanities Center, Yale University, in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Musicologist and cultural theorist Tomlinson named director of Whitney Humanities Center|url=http://news.yale.edu/2012/04/23/musicologist-and-cultural-theorist-tomlinson-named-director-whitney-humanities-center|website=YaleNews|accessdate=12 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nTomlinson's research has ranged across diverse fields, including the history of opera, early-modern European musical thought and practice, the musical cultures of indigenous American societies, and the philosophy of history and critical theory.  His latest research concerns music, culture, and human evolution.  Here he is concerned to reshape the relations of evolutionary theory, archaeology, and humanistic theory so as to offer a novel model of the emergence of human modernity.  The chief ingredients of his model are the niche-construction theory of biologists' [[extended evolutionary synthesis]], a growing systematization of culture evident in the archaeological record, and an extended semiotics indebted to Charles Sanders Peirce.\n\n==Selected awards==\n*1983\u201384 [[Guggenheim Fellowship]]\n*1988\u201393 [[MacArthur Fellows Program]]\n*2001 Elected to [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n*2010 [[British Academy]], Derek Allen Prize\n*2016 Honorary membership, [[American Musicological Society]]\n\n==Books==\n* [http://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/C/bo28082555.html ''Culture and the Course of Human Evolution''], University of Chicago Press, 2018\n*''A Million Years of Music: The Emergence of Human Modernity'', Zone Books, 2015\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=BvlLbG7a-usC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Gary+A.+Tomlinson&cd=3#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The singing of the New World: indigenous voice in the era of European contact''], Cambridge University Press, 2007, {{ISBN|978-0-521-87391-8}}\n*''Music and Historical Critique: Selected Essays'', Ashgate, 2007\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=Or46P1PEWFgC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Gary+A.+Tomlinson&cd=2#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Metaphysical song: an essay on opera''], Princeton University Press, 1999, {{ISBN|978-0-691-00409-9}} \n*''Music in renaissance magic: toward a historiography of others'', University of Chicago Press, 1993\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=CBzyLholjxoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Monteverdi and the end of the Renaissance''], University of California Press, 1987\n* (with [[Joseph Kerman]]) ''Listen'', sixth edn., Bedford/St.Martin's, 2008\n*Ed., ''Italian Secular Song, 1606\u20131636'', 7 vols., Garland, 1987\u201388\n*Ed., ''Strunk's Source readings in Music History'', revised edition, ''The Renaissance'', Norton, 1998\n\n==Selected Essays==\n*\"Two Deep-Historical Models of Climate Crisis,\" ''South Atlantic Quarterly'' 116 (2017)\n*\"Sound, Affect, and Musicking before the Human,\" ''boundary 2'' 43 (2016)\n*\"Evolutionary Studies in the Humanities: The Case of Music,\" ''Critical Inquiry'' 39 (2013)\n*\"Parahuman Wagnerism,\" ''The Opera Quarterly'' 29 (2013)\n*\"''Il faut mediterraniser la musique'': After Braudel,\" in ''Braudel Revisited: The Mediterranean World, 1600\u20131800'' (University of Toronto Press, 2010)\n*\"''Hamlet'' and ''Poppea'': Musicking Benjamin's ''Trauerspiel'',\" in ''The Opera Quarterly'' 25 (2009)\n*\"Monumental Musicology,\" review essay of Richard Taruskin, ''The Oxford History of Western Music'', in ''Journal of the Royal Musical Association'' 132 (2007)\n*\"Musicology, Anthropology, History,\" in ''The Cultural Study of Music'' (Rutledge, 2003, 2011)\n*\"Vico's Songs: Detours at the Origins of Ethnomusicology,\" in ''The Musical Quarterly'' 83 (1999)\n*\"Ideologies of Aztec Song,\" in ''Journal of the American Musicological Society'' 48 (1995)\n*\"Musical Pasts and Postmodern Musicologies: A Response to Lawrence Kramer,\" in ''Current Musicology'' 53 (1993)\n*\"Cultural Dialogics and Jazz: A White Historian Signifies,\" in ''Black Music Research Journal'' 11 (1991)\n*\"Italian Romanticism and Italian Opera: An Essay in Their Affinities,\" in ''19th-Century Music'' 9 (1986)\n*\"The Web of Culture: A Context for Musicology,\" in ''19th-Century Music'' 7 (1984)\n*\"Madrigal, Monody, and Monteverdi's ''via naturale alla immitatione'',\" ''Journal of the American Musicological Society'' 34 (1981)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100221031728/http://www.upenn.edu/pennnews/current/interviews/011008-1.html \"Where it all began\"], ''Penn Current'', Jan. 10, 2008.\n\n{{Derek Allen Prize}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tomlinson, Gary A}}\n[[Category:American musicologists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n[[Category:MacArthur Fellows]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n", "text_old": "'''Gary Alfred Tomlinson''' (born December 4, 1951) is an American [[musicologist]] and the John Hay Whitney Professor of Music and Humanities at [[Yale University]]. He was formerly the Annenberg Professor in the Humanities at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sas.upenn.edu/music/faculty/history.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-04-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100402075218/http://www.sas.upenn.edu/music/faculty/history.html |archive-date=2010-04-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He graduated from the [[University of California, Berkeley]], with a Ph.D., in 1979 with thesis titled ''Rinuccini, Peri, Monteverdi, and the humanist heritage of opera''.\n\nTomlinson became Director of the Whitney Humanities Center, Yale University, in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Musicologist and cultural theorist Tomlinson named director of Whitney Humanities Center|url=http://news.yale.edu/2012/04/23/musicologist-and-cultural-theorist-tomlinson-named-director-whitney-humanities-center|website=YaleNews|accessdate=12 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nTomlinson's research has ranged across diverse fields, including the history of opera, early-modern European musical thought and practice, the musical cultures of indigenous American societies, and the philosophy of history and critical theory.  His latest research concerns music, culture, and human evolution.  Here he is concerned to reshape the relations of evolutionary theory, archaeology, and humanistic theory so as to offer a novel model of the emergence of human modernity.  The chief ingredients of his model are the niche-construction theory of biologists' [[extended evolutionary synthesis]], a growing systematization of culture evident in the archaeological record, and an extended semiotics indebted to Charles Sanders Peirce.\n\n==Selected Awards==\n*1983-84 [[Guggenheim Fellowship]]\n*1988-93 [[MacArthur Fellows Program]]\n*2001 Elected to [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n*2010 [[British Academy]], Derek Allen Prize\n*2016 Honorary membership, [[American Musicological Society]]\n\n==Books==\n* [http://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/C/bo28082555.html ''Culture and the Course of Human Evolution''], University of Chicago Press, 2018\n*''A Million Years of Music: The Emergence of Human Modernity'', Zone Books, 2015\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=BvlLbG7a-usC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Gary+A.+Tomlinson&cd=3#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The singing of the New World: indigenous voice in the era of European contact''], Cambridge University Press, 2007, {{ISBN|978-0-521-87391-8}}\n*''Music and Historical Critique: Selected Essays'', Ashgate, 2007\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=Or46P1PEWFgC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Gary+A.+Tomlinson&cd=2#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Metaphysical song: an essay on opera''], Princeton University Press, 1999, {{ISBN|978-0-691-00409-9}} \n*''Music in renaissance magic: toward a historiography of others'', University of Chicago Press, 1993\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=CBzyLholjxoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Monteverdi and the end of the Renaissance''], University of California Press, 1987\n* (with [[Joseph Kerman]]) ''Listen'', sixth edn., Bedford/St.Martin's, 2008\n*Ed., ''Italian Secular Song, 1606-1636'', 7 vols., Garland, 1987\u201388\n*Ed., ''Strunk's Source readings in Music History'', revised edition, ''The Renaissance'', Norton, 1998\n\n==Selected Essays==\n*\"Two Deep-Historical Models of Climate Crisis,\" ''South Atlantic Quarterly'' 116 (2017)\n*\"Sound, Affect, and Musicking before the Human,\" ''boundary 2'' 43 (2016)\n*\"Evolutionary Studies in the Humanities: The Case of Music,\" ''Critical Inquiry'' 39 (2013)\n*\"Parahuman Wagnerism,\" ''The Opera Quarterly'' 29 (2013)\n*\"''Il faut mediterraniser la musique'': After Braudel,\" in ''Braudel Revisited: The Mediterranean World, 1600-1800'' (University of Toronto Press, 2010)\n*\"''Hamlet'' and ''Poppea'': Musicking Benjamin's ''Trauerspiel'',\" in ''The Opera Quarterly'' 25 (2009)\n*\"Monumental Musicology,\" review essay of Richard Taruskin, ''The Oxford History of Western Music'', in ''Journal of the Royal Musical Association'' 132 (2007)\n*\"Musicology, Anthropology, History,\" in ''The Cultural Study of Music'' (Rutledge, 2003, 2011)\n*\"Vico's Songs: Detours at the Origins of Ethnomusicology,\" in ''The Musical Quarterly'' 83 (1999)\n*\"Ideologies of Aztec Song,\" in ''Journal of the American Musicological Society'' 48 (1995)\n*\"Musical Pasts and Postmodern Musicologies: A Response to Lawrence Kramer,\" in ''Current Musicology'' 53 (1993)\n*\"Cultural Dialogics and Jazz: A White Historian Signifies,\" in ''Black Music Research Journal'' 11 (1991)\n*\"Italian Romanticism and Italian Opera: An Essay in Their Affinities,\" in ''19th-Century Music'' 9 (1986)\n*\"The Web of Culture: A Context for Musicology,\" in ''19th-Century Music'' 7 (1984)\n*\"Madrigal, Monody, and Monteverdi's ''via naturale alla immitatione'',\" ''Journal of the American Musicological Society'' 34 (1981)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100221031728/http://www.upenn.edu/pennnews/current/interviews/011008-1.html \"Where it all began\"], ''Penn Current'', Jan. 10, 2008.\n\n{{Derek Allen Prize}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tomlinson, Gary A}}\n[[Category:American musicologists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n[[Category:MacArthur Fellows]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: 1983-84 \u2192 1983\u201384 (4), Awards \u2192 awards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gary_Tomlinson"}
{"title_page": "Feast of Friends", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Feast of Friends\n| image          = \n| caption        =  \n| director       = [[Paul Ferrara]]\n| producer       = [[The Doors]], John Albarian, Matt Friedman\n| writer         =  \n| starring       = [[The Doors]]\n| music          = [[The Doors]]\n| cinematography = [[Paul Ferrara]]\n| editing        = [[Frank Lisciandro]]\n| studio         = Eagle Rock\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|1969|09|29|New York Film Festival|2014|11}}\n| runtime        = 50 minutes (1969 version)<br>144 minutes (2014 version)\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''Feast of Friends''''' is a 1969 [[documentary film]] about the American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[the Doors]]. It was directed by [[Paul Ferrara]], Babe Hill and [[The Doors]]. Ferrara followed the Doors between April and September 1968, filming excerpts of concert performances, conversations between the band and the band relaxing backstage. Hill recorded the audio using a portable [[Nagra]] recorder.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://raymanzarek.com/?page_id=7425 |title=Feast of Friends |author= |website=raymanzarek.com |date= |publisher= |accessdate=1 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe documentary was never officially completed, although it was shown at film festivals. A restored version was released on DVD and Blu-ray in 2014. \n\n==Cast==\n*[[Jim Morrison]] as himself\n*[[Ray Manzarek]] as himself\n*[[Robby Krieger]] as himself\n*[[John Densmore]] as himself\n\n==Production==\nFilming using 16mm cameras took place during the band\u2019s 1968 summer tour. Although all of the band's [[Hollywood Bowl]] appearance in July 1968 was recorded, few other songs by the Doors were recorded in their entirety. Towards the end of the summer of 1968, the band reviewed the expenditure on the film and halted any further recording. [[Frank Lisciandro]] (who had attended film school at UCLA with Morrison and Manzarek) undertook to create a first cut of the film. The band would then decide whether to continue.\n\nHowever, another event was to have a major impact on the project. At a March 1969 concert in Miami, Morrison was [[The Doors#1969\u20131971|arrested]] after allegedly exposing himself onstage. The film was then cancelled.<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite journal| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-doors-self-made-feast-of-friends-doc-to-finally-come-out-this-fall-77834/ | journal=[[Rolling Stone]] | title=The Doors' Self-Made 'Feast of Friends' Doc to Finally Come Out This Fall | date=September 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Bruce Botnick]], the band\u2019s long-time engineer/co-producer and Anna Coker restored the soundtrack for the 2014 release.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6312081/the-doors-john-densmore-documentary-feast-of-friends |title=The Doors' John Densmore Calls 'Feast of Friends' Documentary 'A Real Deal & Then Some' |author=Gary Graff |website=billboard.com |date=7 November 2014 |publisher= |accessdate=1 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nLisciandro's 50 minute cut was shown at film festivals<ref name=\"RS\"/> including the [[New York Film Festival]] on September 29, 1969.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=October 8, 1969|page=30|title=N.Y. Film Festival Reviews|author=Kent.}}</ref>\n\nThe film was finally released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] in 2014 in a longer version. \n\nThe DVD release includes the 1968 British documentary ''[[The Doors Are Open]]'', a featurette titled ''Feast Of Friends: Encore'' including behind-the-scenes outtakes, as well as additional bonus features.<ref name=\"UCR\">{{cite web |url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/the-doors-feast-of-friends/ |title=Ultimate The Doors: A Feast of Friends DVD Review |author= |website=ultimateclassicrock.com |date= |publisher= |accessdate=1 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIn a review for Ultimate Classic Rock, Dave Swanson wrote; \"The live footage within is simply incredible, and the remastering of both audio and video is as good as it gets. The down side, however, is that a snapshot can only give you so much information.\"<ref name=\"UCR\" /> ''[[Uncut (magazine)|UnCut]]'' wrote the film \"doesn\u2019t have much in the way of narrative, but it makes up for it in sheer beauty, a powerful Doors quality. Notionally an account of the band\u2019s 1968 American tour, in truth that fact is more something that you discover for yourself than from the film.\"<ref name=\"uncut\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/reviews/dvd/the-doors-feast-of-friends |title= The Doors \u2013 Feast Of Friends|author= |website=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |date=13 January  2015 |publisher= |accessdate=1 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{AFI film|18893}}\n*{{imdb title|id= tt0196551}}\n\n{{The Doors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feast of Friends, The Doors}}\n[[Category:1969 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Paul Ferrara]]\n[[Category:The Doors]]\n[[Category:Rockumentaries]]\n[[Category:1960s documentary films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Feast of Friends\n| image          = \n| caption        =  \n| director       = [[Paul Ferrara]]\n| producer       = [[The Doors]], John Albarian, Matt Friedman\n| writer         =  \n| starring       = [[The Doors]]\n| music          = [[The Doors]]\n| cinematography = [[Paul Ferrara]]\n| editing        = [[Frank Lisciandro]]\n| studio         = Eagle Rock\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|1969|09|29|New York Film Festival|2014|11}}\n| runtime        = 50 minutes (1969 version)<br>144 minutes (2014 version)\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''Feast of Friends''''' is a 1969 [[documentary film]] about the American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[the Doors]]. It was directed by [[Paul Ferrara]], Babe Hill and [[The Doors]]. Ferrara followed the Doors between April and September 1968, filming excerpts of concert performances, conversations between the band and the band relaxing backstage. Hill recorded the audio using a portable [[Nagra]] recorder.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://raymanzarek.com/?page_id=7425 |title=Feast of Friends |author= |website=raymanzarek.com |date= |publisher= |accessdate=1 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe documentary was never officially completed, although it was shown at film festivals. A restored version was released on DVD and Blu-ray in 2014. \n\n==Cast==\n*[[Jim Morrison]] as himself\n*[[Ray Manzarek]] as himself\n*[[Robby Krieger]] as himself\n*[[John Densmore]] as himself\n\n==Production==\nFilming using 16mm cameras took place during the band\u2019s 1968 summer tour. Although all of the band's [[Hollywood Bowl]] appearance in July 1968 was recorded, few other songs by the Doors were recorded in their entirety. Towards the end of the summer of 1968, the band reviewed the expenditure on the film and halted any further recording. [[Frank Lisciandro]] (who had attended film school at UCLA with Morrison and Manzarek) undertook to create a first cut of the film. The band would then decide whether to continue.\n\nHowever, another event was to have a major impact on the project. At a March 1969 concert in Miami, Morrison was [[The Doors#1969\u20131971|arrested]] after allegedly exposing himself onstage. The film was then cancelled.<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite journal| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-doors-self-made-feast-of-friends-doc-to-finally-come-out-this-fall-77834/ | journal=[[Rolling Stone]] | title=The Doors' Self-Made 'Feast of Friends' Doc to Finally Come Out This Fall | date=September 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Bruce Botnick]], the band\u2019s long-time engineer/co-producer and Anna Coker restored the soundtrack for the 2014 release.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6312081/the-doors-john-densmore-documentary-feast-of-friends |title=The Doors' John Densmore Calls 'Feast of Friends' Documentary 'A Real Deal & Then Some' |author=Gary Graff |website=billboard.com |date=7 November 2014 |publisher= |accessdate=1 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nLisciandro's 50 minute cut was shown at film festivals<ref name=\"RS\"/> including the [[New York Film Festival]] on September 29, 1969.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=October 8, 1969|page=30|title=N.Y. Film Festival Reviews|author=Kent.}}</ref>\n\nThe film was finally released on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] in 2014 in a longer version. \n\nThe DVD release includes the 1968 British documentary ''[[The Doors Are Open]]'', a featurette titled ''Feast Of Friends: Encore'' including behind-the-scenes outtakes, as well as additional bonus features.<ref name=\"UCR\">{{cite web |url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/the-doors-feast-of-friends/ |title=Ultimate The Doors: A Feast of Friends DVD Review |author= |website=ultimateclassicrock.com |date= |publisher= |accessdate=1 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIn a review for Ultimate Classic Rock, Dave Swanson wrote; \"The live footage within is simply incredible, and the remastering of both audio and video is as good as it gets. The down side, however, is that a snapshot can only give you so much information.\"<ref name=\"UCR\" /> ''[[Uncut (magazine)|UnCut]]'' wrote the film \"doesn\u2019t have much in the way of narrative, but it makes up for it in sheer beauty, a powerful Doors quality. Notionally an account of the band\u2019s 1968 American tour, in truth that fact is more something that you discover for yourself than from the film.\"<ref name=\"uncut\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/reviews/dvd/the-doors-feast-of-friends |title= The Doors \u2013 Feast Of Friends|author= |website=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |date=13 January  2015 |publisher= |accessdate=1 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{AFI film|18893}}\n*{{imdb title|id= tt0196551}}\n\n{{The Doors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feast of Friends, The Doors}}\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Paul Ferrara]]\n[[Category:The Doors]]\n[[Category:Rockumentaries]]\n[[Category:2000s documentary films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n", "name_user": "Bovineboy2008", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix year\u2192\u200ePrincipal cast", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feast_of_Friends"}
{"title_page": "Kevin Heffernan (Gaelic footballer)", "text_new": "{{Use Irish English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox GAA player\n| code           = Football\n| sport          = Gaelic football\n| image          =  \n| name           = Kevin Heffernan\n| irish          = Caoimh\u00edn \u00d3 hIfearn\u00e1in\n| fullname       = Kevin Heffernan\n| birth_place    = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date |df=yes|1929|08|20}}\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2013|1|25|1929|08|20}}\n| death_place    = Dublin, Ireland\n| height         = \n| nickname       = Heffo\n| county         = Dublin\n| province       = Leinster\n| club           = [[St Vincents GAA|St. Vincent's]]\n| clposition     = Forward\n| clubs          = \n| clyears        = 1948\u20131967\n| clapps(points) = \n| clcountyf      = 15\n| clcountyh      = 6\n| clprovince     = \n| clallireland   = \n| counties       = [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]]\n| icposition     = Left Corner Forward\n| icyears        = 1948\u20131962\n| icapps(points) = 115 (52\u2013226)<ref>{{cite news|first=Conor|last=McKeon|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/dublins-alltime-leading-scorers-how-dean-rock-surpassed-bernard-brogan-and-his-own-father-38487313.html|title=Dublin's all-time leading scorers: How Dean Rock surpassed Bernard Brogan - and his own father|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|date=11 September 2019|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n| icprovince     = 4\n| icallireland   = 1\n| nfl            = 3\n| allstars       = \n| clupdate       = \n| icupdate       = \n}} \n'''Kevin Heffernan''' (20 August 1929 \u2013 25 January 2013) was an Irish [[Gaelic football]]er and [[Manager (Gaelic games)|manager]] who played as a left corner-forward for the [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] senior team.\n\nRegarded as one of the greatest Gaelic footballers of all-time, Heffernan made his debut during the [[1948 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1948 championship]] and was a regular member of the starting fifteen until his retirement after the [[1962 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1962 championship]]. During that time he won one [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland]] medal, four [[Leinster Senior Football Championship|Leinster]] medals and three [[National Football League (Ireland)|National League]] medals. An All-Ireland runner-up on one occasion, Heffernan captained the team to the All-Ireland title in 1958.\n\nAt club level Heffernan enjoyed a lengthy career with [[St Vincents GAA|St. Vincent's]]. He won fifteen [[Dublin Senior Football Championship|county football championship]] medals and six [[Dublin Senior Hurling Championship|county hurling championship]] medals.\n\nIn retirement from playing Heffernan became involved in coaching and team management. As Dublin manager he revived the county team and steered them to three All-Ireland titles between 1974 and 1983.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2007/0723/1184965208546.html|title=Comments in the Irish Times|accessdate=23 July 2007 | work=The Irish Times|date=7 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nHeffernan has a number of personal achievements. In 1974 he became the only non-player to be honoured as the [[Texaco Footballer of the Year]]. In 1984 he was named in the left corner-forward position on the GAA's Team of the Century. He was moved to the opposite corner when he was named on the Team of the Millennium in 1999.\n\n==Early and private life==\nKevin Heffernan was born on 20 August 1929 in [[Dublin]]. Unlike many of his contemporaries, he was not born into a [[Gaelic football|football]] background, as his father's interests included hunting and shooting rather than [[Gaelic games]]. Heffernan's family moved to the Marino area of the city when he was very young, and it was here that he first came into contact with both football and [[hurling]]. He later attended Scoil Mhuire and St. Joseph's [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]] school where he made great progress as a hurler and as a footballer. It was in secondary school that he first tasted major success, as he won a Leinster Colleges hurling title in 1945.\n\nBy profession Heffernan was a personnel manager for the [[Electricity Supply Board]] (ESB) and he became Chairman of the [[Labour Court of Ireland|Labour Court]].\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Club===\nHeffernan's club [[hurling]] and [[Gaelic football|football]] career coincided with a hugely successful period in the history of the famous [[St Vincents GAA|St Vincent's]] club in Dublin. In terms of football he won a total of 15 senior [[Dublin Senior Football Championship|county championship]] medals, completing a seven in-a-row 1949 to 1955, a six in-a-row between 1957 and 1962, before winning his 14th and 15th county titles in 1966 and 1967. Heffernan also won six senior [[Dublin Senior Football Championship|county championship]] hurling titles in 1953, 1954, 1955, 1957, 1959 and 1962.\n\n===Inter-county===\nHeffernan played both [[hurling]] and [[Gaelic football|football]] at minor level with [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] in the early 1940s. He had some success at these levels, winning a Leinster minor football medal in 1946 and a Leinster minor hurling medal in 1947. He made his senior debut for the Dublin footballers the same year that he was sitting his [[Irish Leaving Certificate|Leaving Certificate]], breaking his jaw in a game just days before his first exam. In spite of this inauspicious start Heffernan went on to have a distinguished inter-county career.\n\nHeffernan first tasted success in 1948 when he won an [[All-Ireland Junior Football Championship|All-Ireland]] medal with the junior football team. In 1953 he won a [[National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]] before winning a second medal in 1955. Later that same year Heffernan claimed his first [[Leinster Senior Football Championship|Leinster]]; however, his side were later defeated by [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] in the All-Ireland final. Three years later in 1958 Heffernan was captain of Dublin when he won his third National League title as well as a second Leinster title.<ref name=\"Heffo dies\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2013/0125/364557-kevin-heffernan-gaa/|title=Former Dublin footballer and manager Kevin Heffernan dies aged 83|work=RT\u00c9 News|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|date=25 January 2013|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref> He later guided his native-county to an [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland]] victory over [[Derry GAA|Derry]]. Heffernan later won two further Leinster titles in 1959 and 1962, however, there was no further All-Ireland titles. He retired from inter-county football shortly afterwards.\n\n==Managerial career==\n{{Infobox GAA manager \n| name            = Kevin Heffernan\n| irish           =\n| sport           = \n| clyears         = \n| club            = \n| winningclubs    = \n| clallireland    = \n| clprovince      = \n| clcounty        = \n| county          = Dublin\n| icyears         = 1973\u20131976<br>1979\u20131986\n| winningcounties = Dublin\n| icprovince      = 5\n| icallireland    = 3\n| league          = 1/2\n|}}\nFollowing a great inter-county career with [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]], he became [[Manager (Gaelic games)|manager]] of the senior inter-county team in late 1973. The era was dominated by the intense rivalry between Dublin and Kerry. In his first championship season in charge he guided 'the Dubs' to their first [[Leinster Senior Football Championship|Leinster]] and [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland]] titles since 1963. Following the completion of the championship Heffernan became the only non-player to be nominated [[Texaco Footballer of the Year]]. In 1975 Dublin captured a second consecutive Leinster title; however, a young [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] team caught Heffernan's teams in a complacent mood in the subsequent All-Ireland final. Dublin bounced back the following year to win the National League as well as a third Leinster title in-a-row before going on to defeat Kerry in the All-Ireland final.\n\nFollowing this victory Heffernan unexpectedly resigned as manager of Dublin, being replaced by [[Tony Hanahoe]] who acted as player-captain-manager. Heffernan returned as manager in 1979 but, after claiming a sixth consecutive Leinster title, lost out to Kerry in the All-Ireland final. Much of the Dublin team fell by the wayside after 1980 but Heffernan built a new team centred on midfield stalwart [[Brian Mullins]] and, in another memorable match remembered mainly for its unsporting conduct, a twelve-man Dublin team to victory over a fourteen-man [[Galway GAA|Galway]] in the All-Ireland Final of 1983. Played in atrocious conditions the referee sent off four players, three of which were from Dublin, and their win saw the team being dubbed 'the twelve apostles'. In January 1986 Heffernan stepped down as Dublin manager.<ref name=\"Poisoned Chalice\">{{cite news |title=New manager must beware of the poisoned chalice |url=http://amp.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/new-manager-must-beware-of-the-poisoned-chalice-26066910.html |accessdate=13 June 2018 |work=amp.independent.ie |date=6 November 2001|first=Martin|last=Breheny|archiveurl=https://amp.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/new-manager-must-beware-of-the-poisoned-chalice-26066910.html |archivedate=6 November 2001}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement and death==\nFollowing his retirement from inter-county management Heffernan continued to have a keen involvement in Gaelic football. In 1984, the GAA's centenary year he was named in the left corner-forward position on the GAA's [[GAA Football Team of the Century|Football Team of the Century]] before later managing the [[Ireland international rules football team|Ireland]] to victory over [[Australia international rules football team|Australia]] in the [[International Rules Series]] in 1986.\n\nIn 2000, Heffernan's status as one of the greatest players of all-time was further cemented when he was named in the left corner-forward position on the GAA's 'Football Team of the Millennium.' He has also continued his involvement with the [[St Vincents GAA|St Vincent's]] club. In 2004, at the age of 74, Heffernan was in charge of the club's under 15 hurling team, which, with a late free from Oliver McElvaney, won a memorable championship final against Cuala, having defeated Ballyboden in the semi-final. This particular St Vincent's team had never beaten either of those clubs before, showing that Heffernan's management touch had not deserted him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stvincentsgaa.ie/AboutUs.aspx?m=fp|title=Famous Players & Teams|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030145245/http://www.stvincentsgaa.ie/AboutUs.aspx?m=fp|archivedate=30 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2006, he trained the club's minor hurling team.\n\nIn 2005, Heffernan was granted the [[Freedom of the City of Dublin]], placing him in a pantheon that includes [[U2]], [[Nelson Mandela]] and [[Bill Clinton]]. He was also among the 25 recipients of the ''Irish Examiner'' GAA President's Awards for 2006. The ceremony which was presented by the former GAA president [[Se\u00e1n Kelly (Irish politician)|Se\u00e1n Kelly]], took place on 31 March 2006.\n\nHeffernan was a consultant to the management of the [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] minor football team for 2007. His appointment received overwhelming approval{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} from the Dublin County Board and he was working with the Dublin minor boss Timmy McCarthy and his managerial colleagues John Archibald and John Lowndes in an advisory capacity for the young Dubs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://breakingnews.iol.ie/sport/story.asp?j=195250654&p=y95z5y36x&t=gaa|title='Heffo' to help Dublin minors|work=Breaking News|date=13 September 2006|accessdate=13 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nHeffernan died in January 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2013/0125/1224329289193.html|title=Dublin legend Kevin Heffernan dies|newspaper=The Irish Times|publisher=Irish Times Trust|date=25 January 2013|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Heffo dies\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/northern-ireland/21204792|title=Dublin GAA legend Kevin Heffernan dies after lengthy illness|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=25 January 2013|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref> At his funeral, attended by huge crowds among them senior politicians, three flags\u2014the Dublin and St Vincent's GAA club flags plus a flag Heffernan got in 2005 when he was awarded the Freedom of Dublin\u2014were put up at the side of the altar; he was buried in Sutton cemetery.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2013/0129/364988-former-dublin-footballer-and-manager-kevin-heffern/|title=Funeral of former Dublin footballer and manager Kevin Heffernan takes place|work=RT\u00c9 News|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|date=29 January 2013|accessdate=29 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* [[Freedom of the City of Dublin]]: 2004<ref>{{cite news|first=James|last=Cox|url=https://www.buzz.ie/gaa/jim-gavin-freedom-dublin-city-338346|title=Jim Gavin will be awarded Freedom of Dublin City|date=23 September 2019|quote=...Freemen and Freewomen including former US presidents John F. Kennedy and Bill Clinton, Nelson Mandela, Mother Teresa and former Dublin Football Manager Kevin Heffernan... GAA icon Kevin Heffernan was ... honoured with the Freedom of the City in 2004.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of people on stamps of Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[List of All-Ireland Senior Football Championship winning captains|All-Ireland Senior Football Final]]<br/>winning [[Captain (sport)|captain]]\n | before = [[Dermot O'Brien]]<br/>([[Louth GAA|Louth]])\n | after  = [[Mick O'Connell]]<br/>([[Kerry GAA|Kerry]])\n | years  = [[1958 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1958]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland Senior Football Final]]<br/>winning [[Manager (Gaelic games)|manager]]\n | before = [[Donie O'Donovan]]<br/>([[Cork GAA|Cork]])\n | after  = [[Mick O'Dwyer]]<br/>([[Kerry GAA|Kerry]])\n | years  = [[1974 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1974]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland Senior Football Final]]<br/>winning [[Manager (Gaelic games)|manager]]\n | before = [[Mick O'Dwyer]]<br/>([[Kerry GAA|Kerry]])\n | after  = [[Tony Hanahoe]]<br/>([[Dublin GAA|Dublin]])\n | years  = [[1976 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1976]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland Senior Football Final]]<br/>winning [[Manager (Gaelic games)|manager]]\n | before = [[Eugene McGee (Gaelic football manager)|Eugene McGee]]<br/>([[Offaly GAA|Offaly]])\n | after  = [[Mick O'Dwyer]]<br/>([[Kerry GAA|Kerry]])\n | years  = [[1983 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1983]]\n}}\n{{s-sports}} \n{{succession box\n | title  = [[List of Dublin senior Gaelic football team captains|Dublin Senior Football Captain]]\n | before = [[Jim Crowley (Gaelic footballer)|Jim Crowley]]\n | after  = [[Ollie Freaney]]\n | years  = 1958\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[List of Dublin senior Gaelic football team captains|Dublin Senior Football Captain]]\n | before =\n | after  = [[Lar Foley]]\n | years  = 1962\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Dublin GAA|Dublin Senior Football Manager]]\n | before = \n | after  = [[Tony Hanahoe]]\n | years  = 1973\u20131976\n}}\n{{succession box\n |title  = [[Dublin GAA|Dublin Senior Football Manager]]\n |before = [[Tony Hanahoe]]\n |after  = [[Brian Mullins]]<br/>[[Robbie Kelleher]]<br/>[[Se\u00e1n Doherty (Gaelic footballer)|Se\u00e1n Doherty]]\n |years  = 1978\u20131985\n}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Texaco Footballer of the Year]]\n | before = [[Billy Morgan (Gaelic footballer)|Billy Morgan]]<br/>([[Cork GAA|Cork]])\n | after  = [[John O'Keeffe (Gaelic footballer)|John O'Keeffe]]<br/>([[Kerry GAA|Kerry]])\n | years  = 1974\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Kevin Heffernan's Teams\n|titlestyle=background:#8CBED6;colour:navy;\n|list1=\n{{All-Ireland Junior Winning Team 1948}}\n{{All-Ireland Winning Team 1958}}\n{{All-Ireland Winning Team 1974}}\n{{All-Ireland Winning Team 1976}}\n{{All-Ireland Winning Team 1983}}\n{{Dublin Gaelic football team managers}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Awards\n|titlestyle=background: gold\n|list1=\n{{Texaco Footballer of the Year}}\n{{Gaelic football Team of the Century}}\n{{Football Team of the Millennium}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heffernan, Kevin}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:All-Ireland-winning captains (football)]]\n[[Category:Dual players]]\n[[Category:Dublin inter-county Gaelic footballers]]\n[[Category:Dublin hurlers]]\n[[Category:Gaelic football forwards]]\n[[Category:Gaelic football managers]]\n[[Category:St Vincents (Dublin) Gaelic footballers]]\n[[Category:St Vincents (Dublin) hurlers]]\n[[Category:Texaco Footballers of the Year]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Irish English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox GAA player\n| code           = Football\n| sport          = Gaelic football\n| image          =  \n| name           = Kevin Heffernan\n| irish          = Caoimh\u00edn \u00d3 hIfearn\u00e1in\n| fullname       = Kevin Heffernan\n| birth_place    = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date |df=yes|1929|08|20}}\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2013|1|25|1929|08|20}}\n| death_place    = Dublin, Ireland\n| height         = \n| nickname       = Heffo\n| county         = Dublin\n| province       = Leinster\n| club           = [[St Vincents GAA|St. Vincent's]]\n| clposition     = Forward\n| clubs          = \n| clyears        = 1948\u20131967\n| clapps(points) = \n| clcountyf      = 15\n| clcountyh      = 6\n| clprovince     = \n| clallireland   = \n| counties       = [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]]\n| icposition     = Left Corner Forward\n| icyears        = 1948\u20131962\n| icapps(points) = 115 (52\u2013226)<ref>{{cite news|first=Conor|last=McKeon|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/dublins-alltime-leading-scorers-how-dean-rock-surpassed-bernard-brogan-and-his-own-father-38487313.html|title=Dublin's all-time leading scorers: How Dean Rock surpassed Bernard Brogan - and his own father|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|date=11 September 2019|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n| icprovince     = 4\n| icallireland   = 1\n| nfl            = 3\n| allstars       = \n| clupdate       = \n| icupdate       = \n}} \n'''Kevin Heffernan''' (20 August 1929 \u2013 25 January 2013) was an Irish [[Gaelic football]]er and [[Manager (Gaelic games)|manager]] who played as a left corner-forward for the [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] senior team.\n\nRegarded as one of the greatest Gaelic footballers of all-time, Heffernan made his debut during the [[1948 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1948 championship]] and was a regular member of the starting fifteen until his retirement after the [[1962 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1962 championship]]. During that time he won one [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland]] medal, four [[Leinster Senior Football Championship|Leinster]] medals and three [[National Football League (Ireland)|National League]] medals. An All-Ireland runner-up on one occasion, Heffernan captained the team to the All-Ireland title in 1958.\n\nAt club level Heffernan enjoyed a lengthy career with [[St Vincents GAA|St. Vincent's]]. He won fifteen [[Dublin Senior Football Championship|county football championship]] medals and six [[Dublin Senior Hurling Championship|county hurling championship]] medals.\n\nIn retirement from playing Heffernan became involved in coaching and team management. As Dublin manager he revived the county team and steered them to three All-Ireland titles between 1974 and 1983.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2007/0723/1184965208546.html|title=Comments in the Irish Times|accessdate=23 July 2007 | work=The Irish Times|date=7 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nHeffernan has a number of personal achievements. In 1974 he became the only non-player to be honoured as the [[Texaco Footballer of the Year]]. In 1984 he was named in the left corner-forward position on the GAA's Team of the Century. He was moved to the opposite corner when he was named on the Team of the Millennium in 1999.\n\n==Early and private life==\nKevin Heffernan was born on 20 August 1929 in [[Dublin]]. Unlike many of his contemporaries, he was not born into a [[Gaelic football|football]] background, as his father's interests included hunting and shooting rather than [[Gaelic games]]. Heffernan's family moved to the Marino area of the city when he was very young, and it was here that he first came into contact with both football and [[hurling]]. He later attended Scoil Mhuire and St. Joseph's [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]] school where he made great progress as a hurler and as a footballer. It was in secondary school that he first tasted major success, as he won a Leinster Colleges hurling title in 1945.\n\nBy profession Heffernan was a personnel manager for the [[Electricity Supply Board]] (ESB) and he became Chairman of the [[Labour Court of Ireland|Labour Court]].\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Club===\nHeffernan's club [[hurling]] and [[Gaelic football|football]] career coincided with a hugely successful period in the history of the famous [[St Vincents GAA|St Vincent's]] club in Dublin. In terms of football he won a total of 15 senior [[Dublin Senior Football Championship|county championship]] medals, completing a seven in-a-row 1949 to 1955, a six in-a-row between 1957 and 1962, before winning his 14th and 15th county titles in 1966 and 1967. Heffernan also won six senior [[Dublin Senior Football Championship|county championship]] hurling titles in 1953, 1954, 1955, 1957, 1959 and 1962.\n\n===Inter-county===\nHeffernan played both [[hurling]] and [[Gaelic football|football]] at minor level with [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] in the early 1940s. He had some success at these levels, winning a Leinster minor football medal in 1946 and a Leinster minor hurling medal in 1947. He made his senior debut for the Dublin footballers the same year that he was sitting his [[Irish Leaving Certificate|Leaving Certificate]], breaking his jaw in a game just days before his first exam. In spite of this inauspicious start Heffernan went on to have a distinguished inter-county career.\n\nHeffernan first tasted success in 1948 when he won an [[All-Ireland Junior Football Championship|All-Ireland]] medal with the junior football team. In 1953 he won a [[National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]] before winning a second medal in 1955. Later that same year Heffernan claimed his first [[Leinster Senior Football Championship|Leinster]]; however, his side were later defeated by [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] in the All-Ireland final. Three years later in 1958 Heffernan was captain of Dublin when he won his third National League title as well as a second Leinster title.<ref name=\"Heffo dies\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2013/0125/364557-kevin-heffernan-gaa/|title=Former Dublin footballer and manager Kevin Heffernan dies aged 83|work=RT\u00c9 News|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|date=25 January 2013|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref> He later guided his native-county to an [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland]] victory over [[Derry GAA|Derry]]. Heffernan later won two further Leinster titles in 1959 and 1962, however, there was no further All-Ireland titles. He retired from inter-county football shortly afterwards.\n\n==Managerial career==\n{{Infobox GAA manager \n| name            = Kevin Heffernan\n| irish           =\n| sport           = \n| clyears         = \n| club            = \n| winningclubs    = \n| clallireland    = \n| clprovince      = \n| clcounty        = \n| county          = Dublin\n| icyears         = 1973\u20131976<br>1979\u20131986\n| winningcounties = Dublin\n| icprovince      = 5\n| icallireland    = 3\n| league          = 1/2\n|}}\nFollowing a great inter-county career with [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]], he became [[Manager (Gaelic games)|manager]] of the senior inter-county team in late 1973. The era was dominated by the intense rivalry between Dublin and Kerry. In his first championship season in charge he guided 'the Dubs' to their first [[Leinster Senior Football Championship|Leinster]] and [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland]] titles since 1963. Following the completion of the championship Heffernan became the only non-player to be nominated [[Texaco Footballer of the Year]]. In 1975 Dublin captured a second consecutive Leinster title; however, a young [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] team caught Heffernan's teams in a complacent mood in the subsequent All-Ireland final. Dublin bounced back the following year to win the National League as well as a third Leinster title in-a-row before going on to defeat Kerry in the All-Ireland final.\n\nFollowing this victory Heffernan unexpectedly resigned as manager of Dublin, being replaced by [[Tony Hanahoe]] who acted as player-captain-manager. Heffernan returned as manager in 1979 but, after claiming a sixth consecutive Leinster title, lost out to Kerry in the All-Ireland final. Much of the Dublin team fell by the wayside after 1980 but Heffernan built a new team centred on midfield stalwart [[Brian Mullins]] and, in another memorable match remembered mainly for its unsporting conduct, a twelve-man Dublin team to victory over a fourteen-man [[Galway GAA|Galway]] in the All-Ireland Final of 1983. Played in atrocious conditions the referee sent off four players, three of which were from Dublin, and their win saw the team being dubbed 'the twelve apostles'. In January 1986 Heffernan stepped down as Dublin manager.<ref name=\"Poisoned Chalice\">{{cite news |title=New manager must beware of the poisoned chalice |url=http://amp.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/new-manager-must-beware-of-the-poisoned-chalice-26066910.html |accessdate=13 June 2018 |work=amp.independent.ie |date=6 November 2001|first=Martin|last=Breheny|archiveurl=https://amp.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/new-manager-must-beware-of-the-poisoned-chalice-26066910.html |archivedate=6 November 2001}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement and death==\nFollowing his retirement from inter-county management Heffernan continued to have a keen involvement in Gaelic football. In 1984, the GAA's centenary year he was named in the left corner-forward position on the GAA's [[GAA Football Team of the Century|Football Team of the Century]] before later managing the [[Ireland international rules football team|Ireland]] to victory over [[Australia international rules football team|Australia]] in the [[International Rules Series]] in 1986.\n\nIn 2000, Heffernan's status as one of the greatest players of all-time was further cemented when he was named in the left corner-forward position on the GAA's 'Football Team of the Millennium.' He has also continued his involvement with the [[St Vincents GAA|St Vincent's]] club. In 2004, at the age of 74, Heffernan was in charge of the club's under 15 hurling team, which, with a late free from Oliver McElvaney, won a memorable championship final against Cuala, having defeated Ballyboden in the semi-final. This particular St Vincent's team had never beaten either of those clubs before, showing that Heffernan's management touch had not deserted him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stvincentsgaa.ie/AboutUs.aspx?m=fp|title=Famous Players & Teams|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030145245/http://www.stvincentsgaa.ie/AboutUs.aspx?m=fp|archivedate=30 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2006, he trained the club's minor hurling team.\n\nIn 2005, Heffernan was granted the [[Freedom of the City of Dublin]], placing him in a pantheon that includes [[U2]], [[Nelson Mandela]] and [[Bill Clinton]]. He was also among the 25 recipients of the ''Irish Examiner'' GAA President's Awards for 2006. The ceremony which was presented by the former GAA president [[Se\u00e1n Kelly (Irish politician)|Se\u00e1n Kelly]], took place on 31 March 2006.\n\nHeffernan was a consultant to the management of the [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] minor football team for 2007. His appointment received overwhelming approval{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} from the Dublin County Board and he was working with the Dublin minor boss Timmy McCarthy and his managerial colleagues John Archibald and John Lowndes in an advisory capacity for the young Dubs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://breakingnews.iol.ie/sport/story.asp?j=195250654&p=y95z5y36x&t=gaa|title='Heffo' to help Dublin minors|work=Breaking News|date=13 September 2006|accessdate=13 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nHeffernan died in January 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2013/0125/1224329289193.html|title=Dublin legend Kevin Heffernan dies|newspaper=The Irish Times|publisher=Irish Times Trust|date=25 January 2013|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Heffo dies\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/northern-ireland/21204792|title=Dublin GAA legend Kevin Heffernan dies after lengthy illness|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=25 January 2013|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref> At his funeral, attended by huge crowds among them senior politicians, three flags\u2014the Dublin and St Vincent's GAA club flags plus a flag Heffernan got in 2005 when he was awarded the Freedom of Dublin\u2014were put up at the side of the altar; he was buried in Sutton cemetery.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2013/0129/364988-former-dublin-footballer-and-manager-kevin-heffern/|title=Funeral of former Dublin footballer and manager Kevin Heffernan takes place|work=RT\u00c9 News|publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|date=29 January 2013|accessdate=29 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* [[Freedom of the City of Dublin]]: 2004<ref>{{cite news|first=James|last=Cox|url=https://www.buzz.ie/gaa/jim-gavin-freedom-dublin-city-338346|title=Jim Gavin will be awarded Freedom of Dublin City|date=23 September 2019|quote=...Freemen and Freewomen including former US presidents John F. Kennedy and Bill Clinton, Nelson Mandela, Mother Teresa and former Dublin Football Manager Kevin Heffernan... GAA icon Kevin Heffernan was ... honoured with the Freedom of the City in 2004.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of people on stamps of Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[List of All-Ireland Senior Football Championship winning captains|All-Ireland Senior Football Final]]<br/>winning [[Captain (sport)|captain]]\n | before = [[Dermot O'Brien]]<br/>([[Louth GAA|Louth]])\n | after  = [[Mick O'Connell]]<br/>([[Kerry GAA|Kerry]])\n | years  = [[1958 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1958]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland Senior Football Final]]<br/>winning [[Manager (Gaelic games)|manager]]\n | before = [[Donie O'Donovan]]<br/>([[Cork GAA|Cork]])\n | after  = [[Mick O'Dwyer]]<br/>([[Kerry GAA|Kerry]])\n | years  = [[1974 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1974]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland Senior Football Final]]<br/>winning [[Manager (Gaelic games)|manager]]\n | before = [[Mick O'Dwyer]]<br/>([[Kerry GAA|Kerry]])\n | after  = [[Tony